{"title_page": "VN-Zoom", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{third-party|date=May 2018}}\n{{Orphan|date=May 2018}}\n{{Copy edit|for=grammar, tenses do not match|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name             = VN-Zoom\n| url              = {{URL|http://vn-zoom.org|vn-zoom.org}}\n| commercial       = No\n| type             = Computer and Technology Forum\n| registration     = Optional{{efn|Registration is required for certain tasks such as creating a new topic, creating a new article in a topic, and viewing web links}}\n| programming_language= [[vBulletin]] for {{URL|http://vn-zoom.com|vn-zoom.com}}<br />[[XenForo]] for {{URL|http://vn-zoom.org|vn-zoom.org}}\n| language         = Vietnamese\n| num_users        = \n| content_license  = \n| owner            = \n| author           = PeMit#1\n| launch_date      = {{Start date|mf=yes|2006|8|03}}\n| alexa            = {{nowrap|{{decrease}} 34,115<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/vn-zoom.com|title=Alexa info for VN-Zoom.com|publisher=[[Alexa Internet|Alexa]]|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> ({{as of|2015|06|16|alt=June 2015}})\n| current status  = Active\n}}\n}}\n\n'''VN-Zoom''' was a [[public]], free-access [[internet forum]] based in Vietnam. It was shut down on November 5, 2018.<ref>http://genk.vn/dien-dan-cong-nghe-vn-zoom-chinh-thuc-dong-cua-sau-12-nam-hoat-dong-20181105123607359.chn</ref>\n\n==Creation==\n''VN-Zoom'' was administrated by Dinh Quang Vinh, <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-zoom.com/f3/vnzoom-thanh-lap-nam-nao-440580.html/|title=Vnzoom th\u00e0nh l\u1eadp n\u0103m n\u00e0o|publisher=cmo on VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> and was created using [[Internet forum software]] [[vBulletin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vn-zoom.com/|title=VN-Zoom Homepage|publisher=VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Content==\n''VN-Zoom'' was a forum about [[computing]] and [[technology]], such as [[Windows (operating system)|Windows]], [[computer hardware]], [[video games]], and [[mobile phones]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-z.vn/|title=VN-Zoom Homepage|publisher=VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> Previously ''VN-Zoom'' was also famous for uploading [[pirated software]]. VN-Zoom matured into a forum for technology news, with tips on information technology and reviews of technological equipment.\n\n==Access and limits==\n''VN-Zoom'' was public and accessible for everyone on [[the Internet]] from Vietnam. Only registered users were able to do certain tasks, such as creating new topics and articles. New users also lacked access to some advanced features of the forum, such as creating a new topic or thanking a person on the forum. Users were required to have created more than 5 articles to send thanks and more than 10 articles to create a new topic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-zoom.com/f3/tut-thu-thuat-khi-post-bai-mot-so-cau-hoi-thuong-gap-cho-nhung-nguoi-moi-lam-quen-voi-v-z-1537093.html/|title=[TUT] Th\u1ee7 thu\u1eadt khi post b\u00e0i l\u00ean VNZ|publisher=Home Sweet Home on VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> Access to ''VN-Zoom'' was restricted to Vietnamese [[IP address|IP addresses]].<ref name=\"H\u1ecfi v\u1ec1 box movies\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-zoom.com/f3/hoi-ve-box-movies-3032101.html#8/|title=H\u1ecfi v\u1ec1 box movies|publisher=jackiephamvn on VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Rules==\n\n===Basic rules===\n''VN-Zoom'' had strict rules. Users found to be in violation of the rules were banned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-zoom.com/f2/|title=N\u1ed9i quy c\u1ee7a VN-Zoom|publisher=VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Spam, Violations and Bans===\nLike many forums on the Internet, users could [[Forum spam|spam]] or create topics or articles that violate the rules of forum easily. If moderators or administrators view topics and identify spam or prohibited topics or articles, they will delete the offending topic or article and ban the user. Normal users can also report a spam article or prohibited topic or article to the moderator. The moderator will review the report and assess whether or not the reported topic or article is indeed spam or prohibited. If it is  spam, or in violation of the rules of forum, the offending user will be banned. Bans vary in length, depending on the seriousness of the violation, but can be permanent. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-zoom.com/f2/quy-dinh-ve-bai-viet-trong-dien-dan-760889.html/|title=Quy \u0111\u1ecbnh v\u1ec1 b\u00e0i vi\u1ebft trong di\u1ec5n \u0111\u00e0n|publisher=Admin of VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\n\n===File sharing===\n''VN-Zoom'' gained notoriety for hosting unauthorized copies of software, games and films. This content was shared by users on the forum and could be downloaded easily. Because of this, ''VN-Zoom'' received several [[DMCA takedown|DMCA copyright claims]] from software publishers.<ref name=\"H\u1ecfi v\u1ec1 box movies\"/>\n\n===Trouble with Google Search===\n''VN-Zoom'' was restricted by [[Google Search]] for its focus on unlicensed distribution. [[Google]] identified ''VN-Zoom'' as a [[Malicious Web Site|malicious website]] and removed ''VN-Zoom'' from its search results. In order to access ''VN-Zoom's'' content in a search, users would need to add the \"vn-zoom\" keyword behind the keyword that they want to find. However, when users click on the ''VN-Zoom'' link from Google in [[Google Chrome]], Google identified ''VN-Zoom'' as a malicious website and recommended that users not visit the page.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-zoom.com/f295/vn-zoom-nen-cai-thien-quan-he-voi-google-3051582.html/|title=Vn-zoom n\u00ean c\u1ea3i thi\u1ec7n quan h\u1ec7 v\u1edbi google|publisher=tiktiktac on VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-zoom.com/f3/co-ai-khac-phuc-duoc-google-chrome-chan-vn-zoom-khong-2975834.html/|title=c\u00f3 ai kh\u1eafc ph\u1ee5c \u0111\u01b0\u1ee3c google chrome ch\u1eb7n vn-zoom ko?|publisher=laobeoIII on VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Internet forums]]\n[[Category:Internet in Vietnam]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{third-party|date=May 2018}}\n{{Orphan|date=May 2018}}\n{{Copy edit|for=grammar, tenses do not match|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name             = VN-Zoom\n| url              = {{URL|http://vn-zoom.org|vn-zoom.org}}\n| commercial       = No\n| type             = Computer and Technology Forum\n| registration     = Optional{{efn|Registration is required for certain tasks such as creating a new topic, creating a new article in a topic, and viewing web links}}\n| programming_language= [[vBulletin]] for {{URL|http://vn-zoom.com|vn-zoom.com}}<br />[[XenForo]] for {{URL|http://vn-zoom.org|vn-zoom.org}}\n| language         = Vietnamese\n| num_users        = \n| content_license  = \n| owner            = \n| author           = PeMit#1\n| launch_date      = {{Start date|mf=yes|2006|8|03}}\n| alexa            = {{nowrap|{{decrease}} 34,115<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/vn-zoom.com|title=Alexa info for VN-Zoom.com|publisher=[[Alexa Internet|Alexa]]|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> ({{as of|2015|06|16|alt=June 2015}})\n| current status  = Active\n}}\n}}\n\n'''VN-Zoom''' was a [[public]], free-access [[internet forum]] based in Vietnam. It was shut down on November 5, 2018.<ref>http://genk.vn/dien-dan-cong-nghe-vn-zoom-chinh-thuc-dong-cua-sau-12-nam-hoat-dong-20181105123607359.chn</ref>\n\n==Creation==\n''VN-Zoom'' was administrated by Dinh Quang Vinh, <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-zoom.com/f3/vnzoom-thanh-lap-nam-nao-440580.html/|title=Vnzoom th\u00e0nh l\u1eadp n\u0103m n\u00e0o|publisher=cmo on VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> and was created using [[Internet forum software]] [[vBulletin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vn-zoom.com/|title=VN-Zoom Homepage|publisher=VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Content==\n''VN-Zoom'' was a forum about [[computing]] and [[technology]], such as [[Windows (operating system)|Windows]], [[computer hardware]], [[video games]], and [[mobile phones]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-z.vn/|title=VN-Zoom Homepage|publisher=VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> Previously ''VN-Zoom'' was also famous for uploading [[pirated software]]. VN-Zoom matured into a forum for technology news, with tips on information technology and reviews of technological equipment.\n\n==Access and limits==\n''VN-Zoom'' was public and accessible for everyone on [[the Internet]] from Vietnam. Only registered users were able to do certain tasks, such as creating new topics and articles. New users also lacked access to some advanced features of the forum, such as creating a new topic or thanking a person on the forum. Users were required to have created more than 5 articles to send thanks and more than 10 articles to create a new topic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-zoom.com/f3/tut-thu-thuat-khi-post-bai-mot-so-cau-hoi-thuong-gap-cho-nhung-nguoi-moi-lam-quen-voi-v-z-1537093.html/|title=[TUT] Th\u1ee7 thu\u1eadt khi post b\u00e0i l\u00ean VNZ|publisher=Home Sweet Home on VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref> Access to ''VN-Zoom'' was restricted to Vietnamese [[IP address|IP addresses]].<ref name=\"H\u1ecfi v\u1ec1 box movies\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-zoom.com/f3/hoi-ve-box-movies-3032101.html#8/|title=H\u1ecfi v\u1ec1 box movies|publisher=jackiephamvn on VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Rules==\n\n===Basic rules===\n''VN-Zoom'' had strict rules. Users found to be in violation of the rules were banned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-zoom.com/f2/|title=N\u1ed9i quy c\u1ee7a VN-Zoom|publisher=VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Spam, Violations and Bans===\nLike many forums on the Internet, users can [[Forum spam|spam]] or create topics or article that violate the rules of forum easily as a new topic or article. If moderators or administrators view topics and identify spam or prohibited topics or articles, they will delete the offending topic or article and ban the user. Normal users can also report a spam article or prohibited topic or article to the moderator. The moderator will review the report and assess whether or not the reported topic or article is indeed spam or prohibited. If it is  spam, or in violation of the rules of forum, the offending user will be banned. Bans vary in length, depending on the seriousness of the violation, but can be permanent. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-zoom.com/f2/quy-dinh-ve-bai-viet-trong-dien-dan-760889.html/|title=Quy \u0111\u1ecbnh v\u1ec1 b\u00e0i vi\u1ebft trong di\u1ec5n \u0111\u00e0n|publisher=Admin of VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\n\n===File sharing===\n''VN-Zoom'' gained notoriety for hosting unauthorized copies of software, games and films. This content was shared by users on the forum and could be downloaded easily. Because of this, ''VN-Zoom'' received several [[DMCA takedown|DMCA copyright claims]] from software publishers.<ref name=\"H\u1ecfi v\u1ec1 box movies\"/>\n\n===Trouble with Google Search===\n''VN-Zoom'' was restricted by [[Google Search]] for its focus on unlicensed distribution. [[Google]] identified ''VN-Zoom'' as a [[Malicious Web Site|malicious website]] and removed ''VN-Zoom'' from its search results. In order to access ''VN-Zoom's'' content in a search, users would need to add the \"vn-zoom\" keyword behind the keyword that they want to find. However, when users click on the ''VN-Zoom'' link from Google in [[Google Chrome]], Google identified ''VN-Zoom'' as a malicious website and recommended that users not visit the page.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-zoom.com/f295/vn-zoom-nen-cai-thien-quan-he-voi-google-3051582.html/|title=Vn-zoom n\u00ean c\u1ea3i thi\u1ec7n quan h\u1ec7 v\u1edbi google|publisher=tiktiktac on VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vn-zoom.com/f3/co-ai-khac-phuc-duoc-google-chrome-chan-vn-zoom-khong-2975834.html/|title=c\u00f3 ai kh\u1eafc ph\u1ee5c \u0111\u01b0\u1ee3c google chrome ch\u1eb7n vn-zoom ko?|publisher=laobeoIII on VN-Zoom|accessdate=July 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Internet forums]]\n[[Category:Internet in Vietnam]]\n", "name_user": "Lilachouse", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSpam, Violations and Bans:Grammar and style", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/VN-Zoom"}
{"title_page": "Online auction", "text_new": "{{Ecommerce}}\nAn '''online auction''' (also electronic auction or E-Auction or e-auction or eAuction) is an [[auction]] which is held over the [[internet]].<ref>{{cite book|title=E-Collaboration und E-Reverse Auctions|last=Kleusberg|first=Peter|year=2009|location=Saarbr\u00fccken|pages=16\u201325}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=E-Sourcing in Procurement|last=Engelbrecht-Wiggans|first=Peter|publisher=Management Science|year=2006|page=581}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=REVERSE AUCTIONS 101|last=Wyld|first=David C.|publisher=Southeastern Louisiana University|year=2012|location=Louisiana}}</ref> Online auctions come in many different formats, but most popularly they are ascending [[English auction]]s, descending [[Dutch auction]]s, [[First-price sealed-bid auction|first-price sealed-bid]], [[Vickrey auction]]s, or sometimes even a combination of multiple auctions, taking elements of one and forging them with another. \n\nThe scope and reach of these auctions have been propelled by the Internet to a level beyond what the initial purveyors had anticipated.<ref name='Insights and analysis of online auctions'>{{Cite journal | last1 = Bapna | first1 = R. | last2 = Goes | first2 = P. | last3 = Gupta | first3 = A. | doi = 10.1145/384150.384160 | title = Insights and analyses of online auctions | journal = Communications of the ACM | volume = 44 | issue = 11 | pages = 42 | year = 2001 | pmid =  | pmc = | citeseerx = 10.1.1.22.1515 }}</ref> This is mainly because online auctions break down and remove the physical limitations of traditional auctions such as geography, presence, time, space, and a small target audience.<ref name='Insights and analysis of online auctions' /> This influx in reachability has also made it easier to commit unlawful actions within an auction.<ref name='Auction Fraud'>{{Cite journal | last1 = Albert | first1 = M. R. | title = E-Buyer Beware: Why Online Auction Fraud Should Be Regulated | doi = 10.1111/j.1744-1714.2002.tb00306.x | journal = American Business Law Journal | volume = 39 | issue = 4 | pages = 575\u2013644 | year = 2002 | pmid =  | pmc = | url = https://scholarlycommons.law.hofstra.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1699&context=faculty_scholarship }}</ref> In 2002, online auctions were projected to account for 30% of all online [[e-commerce]] due to the rapid expansion of the popularity of the form of electronic commerce.''<ref>{{Cite book | last1 = Vakrat | first1 = Y. | last2 = Seidmann | first2 = A. | doi = 10.1109/HICSS.2000.926822 | chapter = Implications of the bidders' arrival process on the design of online auctions | title = Proceedings of the 33rd Annual Hawaii International Conference on System Sciences | pages = 7 | year = 2000 | isbn = 978-0-7695-0493-3 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref>'' Online auctions include business to business (B2B), business to consumer (B2C), and consumer to consumer (C2C) auctions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techopedia.com/definition/26416/online-auction|title=What is an Online Auction? - Definition from Techopedia|website=Techopedia.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe largest online auction site is [[eBay]], which was the first to support person-to-person transactions. Other popular examples of online auction sites include WebStore, OnlineAuction and Overstock.\n\n==History==\n[[World Wide Web|Web]]-based [[e-commerce|online commercial]] activity for online auctions dates back to 1995, when two auction sites were founded independently with alternative business models.<ref name=\"Bunnell\">{{cite book |last1=Bunnell |first1=David |title=The ebay Phenomenon: Business Secrets Behind the World's Hottest Internet Company |date=2001 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |isbn=9780471436799 |pages=71\u201381 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pnict8L-_iYC&pg=PA71 |chapter=The eBay Business Model}}</ref> The first online auction site was [[Onsale.com]], founded by [[Jerry Kaplan]] in May 1995.<ref>{{cite news |title=Auction of Collectibles on the Internet |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/05/23/business/company-news-auction-of-collectibles-on-the-internet.html |accessdate=18 September 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 23, 1995}}</ref> In September that same year, [[eBay]] was founded by French-Iranian computer scientist [[Pierre Omidyar]]. Both of these companies used ascending bid. The Web offered new advantages such as the use of automated bids via electronic forms, a search engine to be able to quickly find items, and the ability to allow users to view items by categories. In contrast to Onsale where the company itself was acting as the seller, eBay was the first online auction site to support person-to-person transactions. This led to eBay becoming the first online auction to draw a mass volume of [[online transactions]], and it had the largest [[e-commerce]] userbase of any site into the 2000s.<ref name=\"Bunnell\"/>\n\nOnline auctions have greatly increased the variety of goods and services that can be bought and sold using auction mechanisms along with expanding the possibilities for the ways auctions can be conducted and in general created new uses for auctions. In the current web environment there are hundreds, if not thousands, of websites dedicated to online auction practices.\n\nHowever, online auctions on websites weren't the first type of online auctions. In fact, before them, online auctions took place through email and bulletin boards. The auctioneer/seller would post a notice on a system bulletin board, describing the item for sale and setting a minimum bid and closing time.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ecommercebytes.com/cab/abu/y206/m08/abu0173/s04|title=The Very First Online Auctions|last=Banks|first=Michael|date=August 20, 2006|website=Ecommerce bytes|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref> CompuServe was sponsoring such auctions through its classified ad system in 1980. But individuals ran their own online auctions as early as 1979 on both CompuServe and The Source, which were in beta the first part of that year. Such auctions were also run on the earliest public BBSes, going back to 1978. <ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Types==\n{{See also|Auction#Types}}\n\n===English auctions===\n\nIn live terms, [[English auction]]s are where bids are announced by either an auctioneer or by the bidders and winners pay what they bid to receive the object. English auctions are claimed to be the most common form of third-party on-line auction format used and is deemed to appear the most simplistic of all the forms.<ref name='managing_online_auctions'>{{Cite journal | last1 = Pinker | first1 = E. J. | last2 = Seidmann | first2 = A. | last3 = Vakrat | first3 = Y. | doi = 10.1287/mnsc.49.11.1457.20584 | title = Managing Online Auctions: Current Business and Research Issues | journal = Management Science | volume = 49 | issue = 11 | pages = 1457 | year = 2003 | pmid =  | pmc = | url = http://www.simon.rochester.edu/fac/pinker/papers/managingonlineauctions.pdf }}</ref> The common operational method of the format is that it is an ascending bid auction in which bids are open for all to see. The winner is the highest bidder and the price is the highest bid.<ref name='managing_online_auctions' /> The popularity of the English auction is due to the fact that it uses a mechanism that people find familiar and intuitive and therefore reduces transaction costs. It also transcends the boundaries of a traditional English auction where physical presence is required by the bidders, making it increasingly popular even though there is a susceptibility to various forms of cheating.<ref name='managing_online_auctions' /> In the ascending-price auction, it is a \u2018dominant strategy\u2019 to stay in the auction until the price reaches the bidder's value.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ockenfels|first=Axel|last2=Reiley|first2=David|last3=Sadrieh|first3=Abdolkarim|date=December 2006|title=Online Auctions|url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w12785}}</ref>\n\n===Dutch auctions===\n[[Dutch auction]]s are the reverse of English auctions whereby the price begins high and is systematically lowered until a buyer accepts the price. Dutch auction services are usually misleading and the term 'Dutch' tends to have become common usage for the use of a [[multiunit auction]] in a single unit auction as opposed to how it is originally intended for that of a declining price auction. However, with actual on-line Dutch auctions where the price is descending, it was found that auctions have on average a 30% higher ending price than first-price auctions with speculation pointing to bidder impatience or the effect of endogenous entry on the Dutch auction.\n\n===First-price sealed-bid===\n[[First-price sealed-bid auction|First-price sealed-bid]] auctions are when a single bid is made by all bidding parties and the single highest bidder wins, and pays what they bid. The main difference between this and [[#English auctions|English auctions]] is that bids are not openly viewable or announced as opposed to the competitive nature which is generated by public bids. From the [[game theory|game-theoretic]] point of view, the first-price sealed-bid auction is strategically equivalent to the [[Dutch auction]]; that is, in both auctions the players will be using the same bidding strategies.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Milgrom|first1=P.|last2=Weber|first2=R.|year=1982|title=A theory of auctions and competitive bidding|journal=Econometrica|volume=50|issue=5|pages=1089&ndash;1122|jstor=1911865|doi=10.2307/1911865|url=http://www.kellogg.northwestern.edu/research/math/papers/447.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Vickrey auction===\nA [[Vickrey auction]], sometimes known as a ''second-price sealed-bid auction'', uses very much the same principle as a first-price sealed bid. However, the highest bidder and winner will only pay what the second highest bidder had bid.   \nThe Vickrey auction is suggested to prevent the incentive for buyers to bid strategically, due to the fact it requires them to speak the truth by giving their true value of the item. If a bidder makes a very high bid, they may have to pay that price, but if they make a low bid there is a chance that they will lose the item. Therefore, the winner is the person who values the item the highest. It's a win-win situation for both the seller and the winner.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Amit|first1=Alon|title=What Is a Vickrey Auction, and How Does It Work?|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/quora/2013/09/09/vickrey_auction_what_is_it_and_why_does_the_winner_pay_the_second_highest.html|website=Slate|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Reverse auction===\n[[Reverse auction]]s are where the roles of buyer and seller are reversed. Multiple sellers compete to obtain the buyer's business and prices typically decrease over time as new offers are made. They do not follow the typical auction format in that the buyer can see all the offers and may choose which they would prefer. Reverse auctions are used predominantly in a business context for [[procurement]].<ref>{{cite journal|jstor= 30040539|date=3 July 2003|author=Jap, Sandy|title=An Exploratory Study of the Introduction of Online Reverse Auctions|journal=Journal of Marketing|volume=67|issue=3|pages=96\u2013107|doi=10.1509/jmkg.67.3.96.18651|citeseerx=10.1.1.196.9582}}</ref> Reverse auctions bring buyers and sellers together in a transparent marketplace. The practice has even been implemented for private jet travel on the online auction site [[Marmalade Skies]].\nIP\nThe term reverse auction is often confused with [[unique bid auction]]s, which are more akin to traditional auctions as there is only one seller and multiple buyers. However, they follow a similar price reduction concept except the lowest unique bid always wins, and each bid is confidential.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prl.aps.org/abstract/PRL/v108/i8/e088701|title=Equilibrium strategy and population-size effects in lowest unique bid auctions|author1=Simone Pigolotti |author2=Sebastian Bernhardsson |author3=Jeppe Juul |author4=Gorm Galster |author5=Pierpaolo Vivo |year=2012|accessdate=2012-10-25}}</ref>\n\n===Bidding fee auction===\nA [[bidding fee auction]] (also known as a penny auction) requires customers to pay for bids, which they can increment an auction price one unit of currency at a time. On [[English auction]]s for example, the price goes up in 1 pence (0.01 GBP) increments. There has been criticism that compares this type of auction to gambling, as users can spend a considerable amount of money without receiving anything in return (other than the spent bids trying to acquire the item).<ref name=\"codinghorror.com\">{{cite web|last=Atwood |first=Jeff |url=http://www.codinghorror.com/blog/archives/001196.html |title=Profitable Until Deemed Illegal |publisher=Coding Horror |date=2008-12-11 |accessdate=2013-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/11/AR2009071100684.html | work=The Washington Post | title=The Big Money: The Pennies Add Up at Swoopo.com | first=Mark | last=Gimein | date=2009-07-12 | accessdate=2010-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Atwood |first=Jeff |url=http://www.codinghorror.com/blog/archives/001261.html |title=Penny Auctions: They're Gambling |publisher=Coding Horror |date=2009-05-25 |accessdate=2013-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://technologizer.com/2008/09/17/is-swoopo-nothing-more-than-a-well-designed-gimmick/ |title=Is Swoopo Nothing More Than a Well-Designed Gimmick? |publisher=Technologizer.com |date=2008-09-17 |accessdate=2013-01-03}}</ref><ref name=\"gambling-msnbc\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20110514150647/http://redtape.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2011/02/18/6345481-an-ipad-for-282-or-illegal-gambling An iPad for $2.82, or illegal gambling?] </ref> <!-- By examining an auction on a popular website that hosts this type of bidding, it can be worked out that the owner typically makes more money than the items actual worth.  -->The auction owner (typically the owner of the website) makes money in two ways, the purchasing of bids and the actual amount made from the final cost of the item. \n<ref name=\"OAR on How Penny Auctions Make Money\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineauctionreviews.org/strategies/auctions-101/ |title=Penny Auctions 101 |publisher=Onlineauctionreviews.org |accessdate=2013-01-03}}</ref>\n\n== Models ==\nIn addition to the basic types of online auctions, there are also two main models.\n\n=== Common-value model ===\nIn this model all individual bidders have different information about the actual value of the object (e.g. whether they think the piece of art is fake or genuine) even though the value is known to every bidder. In this situation bidders typically change their estimates of the value according to the information they get from the behavior of the people they bid against.\n\n=== Private-value model ===\nIn this model information from the competitors is not taken into account when estimating the actual value of the object. In these models, each bidder gets a private signal, and the value to the bidder is a function of all signals.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Bidding Techniques ==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2020}}\n\n=== Auction squatting ===\nIs a technique involving placing early bids and then watching the auction until the very end. The main tactic is to look for other bids in order to be able to match them as fast as possible and more often than any other competitor. This sends a signal of how serious you are about the auction and could scare off the rest of the bidders.\n\n=== Auction sniping ===\nA strategy involving waiting up until the last seconds of an online auction and then submitting your bid with a goal of \u201cstealing\u201d the auction from everyone else.\n\nIt is not possible to perform this technique on every online auction, most of them will extend time if there is a bid with only a few seconds left. Even with this precaution of auction sites, auction sniping is still a very successful tool used to win.\n\n=== Beginning with a high bid ===\nIn some cases, the best strategy is to put a high bid first instead of starting off with low bids. Low bids might achieve a lower price, but on the other hand invite more bidders, whereas directly stating your value of the object by putting a high bid right from the start might intimidate the competition.\n\n== Legalities ==\n\n=== Shill bidding ===\n\nPlacing fake bids that benefits the seller of the item is known as [[shill bidding]]. This is a method often used in online auctions but can also happen in standard auctions. This is seen as an unlawful act as it unfairly raises the final price of the auction, so that the winning bidder pays more than they should have. If the shill bid is unsuccessful, the item owner needs to pay the auction fees. In 2011, a member of [[eBay]] became the first individual to be convicted of shill bidding on an auction.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/hi/technology/newsid_10500000/newsid_10508900/10508913.stm|title=Man fined over fake eBay auctions|publisher=BBC|date=2010-07-05}}</ref> By taking part in the process, an individual is breaking the [[Unfair Commercial Practices Directive|European Union fair trading rules]] which carries out a fine of up to \u00a35,000 in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8632357.stm|title=Warning over eBay bidding trick|publisher=BBC|date=2010-04-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Shield bidding ===\nA technique involving a buyer using another account (called a \u201cshield\u201d) to discourage other competitors from bidding by artificially increasing the price and then at the last moment withdrawing their bid to allow the actual buyer to win the auction with a lower price. Most online auction sites don't allow withdrawing bids, therefore making this technique impossible to perform. Although this doesn't stop people from taking advantage of sites where this rule is not implemented. Of course, it's hard for an online auction user to spot a shill or a shield through the faceless online world<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.garage.com/resources/reference-library/internet-law/the-hazards-of-online-auctions/|title=The Hazards of Online Auctions|website=Garage Technology Ventures|language=en|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\n===Spotting Shills and Shields ===\nIt is not an easy task to spot a dirty technique being used by someone basically anonymous in online auctions, but it is certainly doable. It can be revealed by examining all previous seller's sales and looking for an account which has bid on every or almost every auction of this seller. If there is someone suspicious like that, it is most probably a shill using the account to increase the price.\n\nA shield can be spotted similarly to a shill. By doing a search of a person's all won auctions it can be found out whether there is another account participating in exactly the same auctions without ever winning anything, or not. If there is, it is possible that the person is using a shield to help him be successful in auctions.\n\n===Fraud===\nThe increasing popularity of using online auctions has led to an increase in fraudulent activity.<ref name=\"Auction Fraud\"/> This is usually performed on an auction website by creating a very appetizing auction, such as a low starting amount. Once a buyer wins an auction and pays for it, the fraudulent seller will either not pursue with the delivery,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineauctionreviews.org/penny-auction-scams/|title=Auction Scams|publisher=OnlineAuctionReviews.org}}</ref> or send a less valuable version of the purchased item (replicated, used, refurbished, etc.). Protection to prevent such acts has become readily available, most notably [[PayPal#Safety and protection policies|PayPal's buyer protection policy]]. As PayPal handles the transaction, they have the ability to hold funds until a conclusion is drawn whereby the victim can be compensated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paypal.com/uk/helpscr?cmd=_help&locale=en_GB&countrycode=GB&_dyncharset=UTF-8&t=solutionTab&ps=solutionPanels&solutionId=17257|title=What is PayPal Buyer Protection?|publisher=PayPal}}</ref>\n\n===Sale of stolen goods===\nOnline auction websites are used by thieves or [[Fence (criminal)|fences]] to sell stolen goods to unsuspecting buyers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-120375160.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130125090715/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-120375160.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-01-25|title=Stolen-Property Purchases Leave Ebay Buyers Burned.|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=2002-06-11}}</ref> According to police statistics there were over 8000 crimes involving stolen goods, fraud or deception reported on eBay in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ebay: Brisk Bidding in stolen goods|newspaper=The Sunday Times|date=2009-04-11}}</ref> It has become common practice for organised criminals to steal in-demand items, often in bulk. These items are then sold online as it is a safer option due to the anonymity and worldwide market it provides.<ref>{{cite news|title=Target, other stores battle theft rings fencing stolen goods on Web|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=2011-05-06|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2014975231_storetheft06.html?syndication=rss}}</ref> Auction fraud makes up a large percentage of complaints received by the [[FBI]]\u2019s Internet Crime Complaint Center (IC3). This was around 45% in 2006 and 63% in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkworld.com/community/node/18955|title=FBI targets online auction sites' criminal constituency|publisher=networkworld|date=2007-08-31}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Auto auction]]\n* [[Online auction tools]]\n* [[Online travel auction]]\n* [[Tendering]]\n* [[Unique bid auction]]\n* [[Private_electronic_market|Private electronic market]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Auctions]]\n[[Category:American inventions]]\n[[Category:French inventions]]\n[[Category:Iranian inventions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Ecommerce}}\nAn '''online auction''' (also electronic auction or E-Auction or e-auction or eAuction) is an [[auction]] which is held over the [[internet]].<ref>{{cite book|title=E-Collaboration und E-Reverse Auctions|last=Kleusberg|first=Peter|year=2009|location=Saarbr\u00fccken|pages=16\u201325}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=E-Sourcing in Procurement|last=Engelbrecht-Wiggans|first=Peter|publisher=Management Science|year=2006|page=581}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=REVERSE AUCTIONS 101|last=Wyld|first=David C.|publisher=Southeastern Louisiana University|year=2012|location=Louisiana}}</ref> Online auctions come in many different formats, but most popularly they are ascending [[English auction]]s, descending [[Dutch auction]]s, [[First-price sealed-bid auction|first-price sealed-bid]], [[Vickrey auction]]s, or sometimes even a combination of multiple auctions, taking elements of one and forging them with another. \n\nThe scope and reach of these auctions have been propelled by the Internet to a level beyond what the initial purveyors had anticipated.<ref name='Insights and analysis of online auctions'>{{Cite journal | last1 = Bapna | first1 = R. | last2 = Goes | first2 = P. | last3 = Gupta | first3 = A. | doi = 10.1145/384150.384160 | title = Insights and analyses of online auctions | journal = Communications of the ACM | volume = 44 | issue = 11 | pages = 42 | year = 2001 | pmid =  | pmc = | citeseerx = 10.1.1.22.1515 }}</ref> This is mainly because online auctions break down and remove the physical limitations of traditional auctions such as geography, presence, time, space, and a small target audience.<ref name='Insights and analysis of online auctions' /> This influx in reachability has also made it easier to commit unlawful actions within an auction.<ref name='Auction Fraud'>{{Cite journal | last1 = Albert | first1 = M. R. | title = E-Buyer Beware: Why Online Auction Fraud Should Be Regulated | doi = 10.1111/j.1744-1714.2002.tb00306.x | journal = American Business Law Journal | volume = 39 | issue = 4 | pages = 575\u2013644 | year = 2002 | pmid =  | pmc = | url = https://scholarlycommons.law.hofstra.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1699&context=faculty_scholarship }}</ref> In 2002, online auctions were projected to account for 30% of all online [[e-commerce]] due to the rapid expansion of the popularity of the form of electronic commerce.''<ref>{{Cite book | last1 = Vakrat | first1 = Y. | last2 = Seidmann | first2 = A. | doi = 10.1109/HICSS.2000.926822 | chapter = Implications of the bidders' arrival process on the design of online auctions | title = Proceedings of the 33rd Annual Hawaii International Conference on System Sciences | pages = 7 | year = 2000 | isbn = 978-0-7695-0493-3 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref>'' Online auctions include business to business (B2B), business to consumer (B2C), and consumer to consumer (C2C) auctions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techopedia.com/definition/26416/online-auction|title=What is an Online Auction? - Definition from Techopedia|website=Techopedia.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\nThe largest online auction site is [[eBay]], which was the first to support person-to-person transactions. Other popular examples of online auction sites include WebStore, OnlineAuction and Overstock.\n\n==History==\n[[World Wide Web|Web]]-based [[e-commerce|online commercial]] activity for online auctions dates back to 1995, when two auction sites were founded independently with alternative business models.<ref name=\"Bunnell\">{{cite book |last1=Bunnell |first1=David |title=The ebay Phenomenon: Business Secrets Behind the World's Hottest Internet Company |date=2001 |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |isbn=9780471436799 |pages=71\u201381 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pnict8L-_iYC&pg=PA71 |chapter=The eBay Business Model}}</ref> The first online auction site was Onsale, founded by [[Jerry Kaplan]] in May 1995.<ref>{{cite news |title=Auction of Collectibles on the Internet |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/05/23/business/company-news-auction-of-collectibles-on-the-internet.html |accessdate=18 September 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 23, 1995}}</ref> In September that same year, [[eBay]] was founded by French-Iranian computer scientist [[Pierre Omidyar]]. Both of these companies used ascending bid. The Web offered new advantages such as the use of automated bids via electronic forms, a search engine to be able to quickly find items, and the ability to allow users to view items by categories. In contrast to Onsale where the company itself was acting as the seller, eBay was the first online auction site to support person-to-person transactions. This led to eBay becoming the first online auction to draw a mass volume of [[online transactions]], and it had the largest [[e-commerce]] userbase of any site into the 2000s.<ref name=\"Bunnell\"/>\n\nOnline auctions have greatly increased the variety of goods and services that can be bought and sold using auction mechanisms along with expanding the possibilities for the ways auctions can be conducted and in general created new uses for auctions. In the current web environment there are hundreds, if not thousands, of websites dedicated to online auction practices.\n\nHowever, online auctions on websites weren't the first type of online auctions. In fact, before them, online auctions took place through email and bulletin boards. The auctioneer/seller would post a notice on a system bulletin board, describing the item for sale and setting a minimum bid and closing time.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.ecommercebytes.com/cab/abu/y206/m08/abu0173/s04|title=The Very First Online Auctions|last=Banks|first=Michael|date=August 20, 2006|website=Ecommerce bytes|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref> CompuServe was sponsoring such auctions through its classified ad system in 1980. But individuals ran their own online auctions as early as 1979 on both CompuServe and The Source, which were in beta the first part of that year. Such auctions were also run on the earliest public BBSes, going back to 1978. <ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Types==\n{{See also|Auction#Types}}\n\n===English auctions===\n\nIn live terms, [[English auction]]s are where bids are announced by either an auctioneer or by the bidders and winners pay what they bid to receive the object. English auctions are claimed to be the most common form of third-party on-line auction format used and is deemed to appear the most simplistic of all the forms.<ref name='managing_online_auctions'>{{Cite journal | last1 = Pinker | first1 = E. J. | last2 = Seidmann | first2 = A. | last3 = Vakrat | first3 = Y. | doi = 10.1287/mnsc.49.11.1457.20584 | title = Managing Online Auctions: Current Business and Research Issues | journal = Management Science | volume = 49 | issue = 11 | pages = 1457 | year = 2003 | pmid =  | pmc = | url = http://www.simon.rochester.edu/fac/pinker/papers/managingonlineauctions.pdf }}</ref> The common operational method of the format is that it is an ascending bid auction in which bids are open for all to see. The winner is the highest bidder and the price is the highest bid.<ref name='managing_online_auctions' /> The popularity of the English auction is due to the fact that it uses a mechanism that people find familiar and intuitive and therefore reduces transaction costs. It also transcends the boundaries of a traditional English auction where physical presence is required by the bidders, making it increasingly popular even though there is a susceptibility to various forms of cheating.<ref name='managing_online_auctions' /> In the ascending-price auction, it is a \u2018dominant strategy\u2019 to stay in the auction until the price reaches the bidder's value.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Ockenfels|first=Axel|last2=Reiley|first2=David|last3=Sadrieh|first3=Abdolkarim|date=December 2006|title=Online Auctions|url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w12785}}</ref>\n\n===Dutch auctions===\n[[Dutch auction]]s are the reverse of English auctions whereby the price begins high and is systematically lowered until a buyer accepts the price. Dutch auction services are usually misleading and the term 'Dutch' tends to have become common usage for the use of a [[multiunit auction]] in a single unit auction as opposed to how it is originally intended for that of a declining price auction. However, with actual on-line Dutch auctions where the price is descending, it was found that auctions have on average a 30% higher ending price than first-price auctions with speculation pointing to bidder impatience or the effect of endogenous entry on the Dutch auction.\n\n===First-price sealed-bid===\n[[First-price sealed-bid auction|First-price sealed-bid]] auctions are when a single bid is made by all bidding parties and the single highest bidder wins, and pays what they bid. The main difference between this and [[#English auctions|English auctions]] is that bids are not openly viewable or announced as opposed to the competitive nature which is generated by public bids. From the [[game theory|game-theoretic]] point of view, the first-price sealed-bid auction is strategically equivalent to the [[Dutch auction]]; that is, in both auctions the players will be using the same bidding strategies.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Milgrom|first1=P.|last2=Weber|first2=R.|year=1982|title=A theory of auctions and competitive bidding|journal=Econometrica|volume=50|issue=5|pages=1089&ndash;1122|jstor=1911865|doi=10.2307/1911865|url=http://www.kellogg.northwestern.edu/research/math/papers/447.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Vickrey auction===\nA [[Vickrey auction]], sometimes known as a ''second-price sealed-bid auction'', uses very much the same principle as a first-price sealed bid. However, the highest bidder and winner will only pay what the second highest bidder had bid.   \nThe Vickrey auction is suggested to prevent the incentive for buyers to bid strategically, due to the fact it requires them to speak the truth by giving their true value of the item. If a bidder makes a very high bid, they may have to pay that price, but if they make a low bid there is a chance that they will lose the item. Therefore, the winner is the person who values the item the highest. It's a win-win situation for both the seller and the winner.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Amit|first1=Alon|title=What Is a Vickrey Auction, and How Does It Work?|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/quora/2013/09/09/vickrey_auction_what_is_it_and_why_does_the_winner_pay_the_second_highest.html|website=Slate|accessdate=27 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Reverse auction===\n[[Reverse auction]]s are where the roles of buyer and seller are reversed. Multiple sellers compete to obtain the buyer's business and prices typically decrease over time as new offers are made. They do not follow the typical auction format in that the buyer can see all the offers and may choose which they would prefer. Reverse auctions are used predominantly in a business context for [[procurement]].<ref>{{cite journal|jstor= 30040539|date=3 July 2003|author=Jap, Sandy|title=An Exploratory Study of the Introduction of Online Reverse Auctions|journal=Journal of Marketing|volume=67|issue=3|pages=96\u2013107|doi=10.1509/jmkg.67.3.96.18651|citeseerx=10.1.1.196.9582}}</ref> Reverse auctions bring buyers and sellers together in a transparent marketplace. The practice has even been implemented for private jet travel on the online auction site [[Marmalade Skies]].\nIP\nThe term reverse auction is often confused with [[unique bid auction]]s, which are more akin to traditional auctions as there is only one seller and multiple buyers. However, they follow a similar price reduction concept except the lowest unique bid always wins, and each bid is confidential.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prl.aps.org/abstract/PRL/v108/i8/e088701|title=Equilibrium strategy and population-size effects in lowest unique bid auctions|author1=Simone Pigolotti |author2=Sebastian Bernhardsson |author3=Jeppe Juul |author4=Gorm Galster |author5=Pierpaolo Vivo |year=2012|accessdate=2012-10-25}}</ref>\n\n===Bidding fee auction===\nA [[bidding fee auction]] (also known as a penny auction) requires customers to pay for bids, which they can increment an auction price one unit of currency at a time. On [[English auction]]s for example, the price goes up in 1 pence (0.01 GBP) increments. There has been criticism that compares this type of auction to gambling, as users can spend a considerable amount of money without receiving anything in return (other than the spent bids trying to acquire the item).<ref name=\"codinghorror.com\">{{cite web|last=Atwood |first=Jeff |url=http://www.codinghorror.com/blog/archives/001196.html |title=Profitable Until Deemed Illegal |publisher=Coding Horror |date=2008-12-11 |accessdate=2013-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/11/AR2009071100684.html | work=The Washington Post | title=The Big Money: The Pennies Add Up at Swoopo.com | first=Mark | last=Gimein | date=2009-07-12 | accessdate=2010-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Atwood |first=Jeff |url=http://www.codinghorror.com/blog/archives/001261.html |title=Penny Auctions: They're Gambling |publisher=Coding Horror |date=2009-05-25 |accessdate=2013-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://technologizer.com/2008/09/17/is-swoopo-nothing-more-than-a-well-designed-gimmick/ |title=Is Swoopo Nothing More Than a Well-Designed Gimmick? |publisher=Technologizer.com |date=2008-09-17 |accessdate=2013-01-03}}</ref><ref name=\"gambling-msnbc\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20110514150647/http://redtape.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2011/02/18/6345481-an-ipad-for-282-or-illegal-gambling An iPad for $2.82, or illegal gambling?] </ref> <!-- By examining an auction on a popular website that hosts this type of bidding, it can be worked out that the owner typically makes more money than the items actual worth.  -->The auction owner (typically the owner of the website) makes money in two ways, the purchasing of bids and the actual amount made from the final cost of the item. \n<ref name=\"OAR on How Penny Auctions Make Money\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineauctionreviews.org/strategies/auctions-101/ |title=Penny Auctions 101 |publisher=Onlineauctionreviews.org |accessdate=2013-01-03}}</ref>\n\n== Models ==\nIn addition to the basic types of online auctions, there are also two main models.\n\n=== Common-value model ===\nIn this model all individual bidders have different information about the actual value of the object (e.g. whether they think the piece of art is fake or genuine) even though the value is known to every bidder. In this situation bidders typically change their estimates of the value according to the information they get from the behavior of the people they bid against.\n\n=== Private-value model ===\nIn this model information from the competitors is not taken into account when estimating the actual value of the object. In these models, each bidder gets a private signal, and the value to the bidder is a function of all signals.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Bidding Techniques ==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=February 2020}}\n\n=== Auction squatting ===\nIs a technique involving placing early bids and then watching the auction until the very end. The main tactic is to look for other bids in order to be able to match them as fast as possible and more often than any other competitor. This sends a signal of how serious you are about the auction and could scare off the rest of the bidders.\n\n=== Auction sniping ===\nA strategy involving waiting up until the last seconds of an online auction and then submitting your bid with a goal of \u201cstealing\u201d the auction from everyone else.\n\nIt is not possible to perform this technique on every online auction, most of them will extend time if there is a bid with only a few seconds left. Even with this precaution of auction sites, auction sniping is still a very successful tool used to win.\n\n=== Beginning with a high bid ===\nIn some cases, the best strategy is to put a high bid first instead of starting off with low bids. Low bids might achieve a lower price, but on the other hand invite more bidders, whereas directly stating your value of the object by putting a high bid right from the start might intimidate the competition.\n\n== Legalities ==\n\n=== Shill bidding ===\n\nPlacing fake bids that benefits the seller of the item is known as [[shill bidding]]. This is a method often used in online auctions but can also happen in standard auctions. This is seen as an unlawful act as it unfairly raises the final price of the auction, so that the winning bidder pays more than they should have. If the shill bid is unsuccessful, the item owner needs to pay the auction fees. In 2011, a member of [[eBay]] became the first individual to be convicted of shill bidding on an auction.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/hi/technology/newsid_10500000/newsid_10508900/10508913.stm|title=Man fined over fake eBay auctions|publisher=BBC|date=2010-07-05}}</ref> By taking part in the process, an individual is breaking the [[Unfair Commercial Practices Directive|European Union fair trading rules]] which carries out a fine of up to \u00a35,000 in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8632357.stm|title=Warning over eBay bidding trick|publisher=BBC|date=2010-04-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Shield bidding ===\nA technique involving a buyer using another account (called a \u201cshield\u201d) to discourage other competitors from bidding by artificially increasing the price and then at the last moment withdrawing their bid to allow the actual buyer to win the auction with a lower price. Most online auction sites don't allow withdrawing bids, therefore making this technique impossible to perform. Although this doesn't stop people from taking advantage of sites where this rule is not implemented. Of course, it's hard for an online auction user to spot a shill or a shield through the faceless online world<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.garage.com/resources/reference-library/internet-law/the-hazards-of-online-auctions/|title=The Hazards of Online Auctions|website=Garage Technology Ventures|language=en|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\n===Spotting Shills and Shields ===\nIt is not an easy task to spot a dirty technique being used by someone basically anonymous in online auctions, but it is certainly doable. It can be revealed by examining all previous seller's sales and looking for an account which has bid on every or almost every auction of this seller. If there is someone suspicious like that, it is most probably a shill using the account to increase the price.\n\nA shield can be spotted similarly to a shill. By doing a search of a person's all won auctions it can be found out whether there is another account participating in exactly the same auctions without ever winning anything, or not. If there is, it is possible that the person is using a shield to help him be successful in auctions.\n\n===Fraud===\nThe increasing popularity of using online auctions has led to an increase in fraudulent activity.<ref name=\"Auction Fraud\"/> This is usually performed on an auction website by creating a very appetizing auction, such as a low starting amount. Once a buyer wins an auction and pays for it, the fraudulent seller will either not pursue with the delivery,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineauctionreviews.org/penny-auction-scams/|title=Auction Scams|publisher=OnlineAuctionReviews.org}}</ref> or send a less valuable version of the purchased item (replicated, used, refurbished, etc.). Protection to prevent such acts has become readily available, most notably [[PayPal#Safety and protection policies|PayPal's buyer protection policy]]. As PayPal handles the transaction, they have the ability to hold funds until a conclusion is drawn whereby the victim can be compensated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.paypal.com/uk/helpscr?cmd=_help&locale=en_GB&countrycode=GB&_dyncharset=UTF-8&t=solutionTab&ps=solutionPanels&solutionId=17257|title=What is PayPal Buyer Protection?|publisher=PayPal}}</ref>\n\n===Sale of stolen goods===\nOnline auction websites are used by thieves or [[Fence (criminal)|fences]] to sell stolen goods to unsuspecting buyers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-120375160.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130125090715/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-120375160.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-01-25|title=Stolen-Property Purchases Leave Ebay Buyers Burned.|work=San Jose Mercury News|date=2002-06-11}}</ref> According to police statistics there were over 8000 crimes involving stolen goods, fraud or deception reported on eBay in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ebay: Brisk Bidding in stolen goods|newspaper=The Sunday Times|date=2009-04-11}}</ref> It has become common practice for organised criminals to steal in-demand items, often in bulk. These items are then sold online as it is a safer option due to the anonymity and worldwide market it provides.<ref>{{cite news|title=Target, other stores battle theft rings fencing stolen goods on Web|newspaper=The Seattle Times|date=2011-05-06|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2014975231_storetheft06.html?syndication=rss}}</ref> Auction fraud makes up a large percentage of complaints received by the [[FBI]]\u2019s Internet Crime Complaint Center (IC3). This was around 45% in 2006 and 63% in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkworld.com/community/node/18955|title=FBI targets online auction sites' criminal constituency|publisher=networkworld|date=2007-08-31}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Auto auction]]\n* [[Online auction tools]]\n* [[Online travel auction]]\n* [[Tendering]]\n* [[Unique bid auction]]\n* [[Private_electronic_market|Private electronic market]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Auctions]]\n[[Category:American inventions]]\n[[Category:French inventions]]\n[[Category:Iranian inventions]]\n", "name_user": "Geysirhead", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Online_auction"}
{"title_page": "Elaine Crowley (presenter)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name             = Elaine Crowley\n| image            = \n| imagesize        = \n| caption          = \n| birthname        = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1977|08|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = Newtwopothouse, [[Mallow, County Cork|Mallow]], [[County Cork]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| education        = [[Dublin Institute of Technology]]\n| occupation       = [[Journalist]], [[News presenter|presenter]], [[News presenter|newsreader]]\n| domestic_partner = \n| years_active     = 2000\u2013present\n| nationality      = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| credits          = ''[[Ireland AM]]''<br>''[[TV3 News]]''<br>''[[Midday (Irish TV series)|Midday]]''<br> [[Elaine (talk show)|Elaine]]\n| URL              = \n}}\n'''Elaine Crowley''' (born 18 August 1977) is an [[Irish people|Irish]] [[journalist]], [[News presenter|presenter]] and [[News presenter|newsreader]], best known for presenting TV3's ''[[Midday (Irish TV series)|Midday]]'' from 2010 to 2016. She currently presents her own titular daytime talkshow ''[[Elaine (talk show)|Elaine]]'' on TV3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundayworld.com/showbiz/brunker-meets.php?aid=4951 |title=TV3 Personality Elaine Crowley |publisher=[[Sunday World]] |accessdate=19 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120514021941/http://www.sundayworld.com/showbiz/brunker-meets.php?aid=4951 |archivedate=14 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCrowley studied at [[Dublin Institute of Technology]] before joining [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] in 2000. She was a newsreader and a presenter on morning talk show ''[[Ireland AM]]'' before headlining panel show ''[[Midday (Irish TV series)|Midday]]'' from 2010 to 2016.\n\n==Personal life==\nCrowley has been open about her struggles with her weight and body image, and with clinical depression.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Horan|first1=Niamh|title=TV3 star Elaine Crowley: 'I'm probably classified as clinically obese but it doesn't bother me anymore'|url=http://www.independent.ie/style/beauty/body/tv3-star-elaine-crowley-im-probably-classified-as-clinically-obese-but-it-doesnt-bother-me-anymore-31209773.html|accessdate=30 June 2016|work=The Irish Independent|date=10 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Quigley|first1=Maeve|title='I was never suicidal but I felt if a bus ran me over it wouldn\u2019t make any difference'|url=http://www.irishmirror.ie/news/tv3-beauty-elaine-crowley-battled-1919888|accessdate=30 June 2016|work=The Irish Mirror|date=30 May 2013}}</ref>\nIn 2016, she took part in ''[[Operation Transformation (TV series)|Celebrity Operation Transformation]]'' on [[RT\u00c9 One]].<ref>{{citeweb|url= http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/television/tv-news/10-things-we-learned-from-celebrity-operation-transformation-35031302.html|title=10 things we learned from Celebrity Operation Transformation|date=7 September 2016|work=Irish Independent|accessdate=8 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n\n==Filmography==\n | 1996\u20131997\n| ''[[Unhappily Ever After]]''\n| Sable O'Brien\n| Recurring role, 19 episodes\n|-Mary O'Hara\n ''[[The Room (2003 film)|The Room]]'' - Lisa's Drug Dealer\n 2003\n | ''[[Battlefield Earth (film)|Battlefield Earth]]''(2000) - Alien taking a dump #3\n 2004\n| ''[[Dark Kingdom: The Dragon King|Ring of the Nibelungs]]'' - Megan, The talking duck\n|  2005\n| ''[[BloodRayne (film)|BloodRayne]]''\n| [[Rayne (BloodRayne)|Rayne]]\n|* ''Double Down'' (2005)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/double_down |title=Double Down (2005) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> - Mary McAffe\n* ''I Am Here.... Now'' (2009) - Woman in Background\n|2009 || ''[[Lesbian Vampire Killers]]'' || Betchy Betick ||\n| ''[[Planet 51]]'' || SKiet (voice) || (2009)\n| \n\n| ''[[S.W.A.T.: Firefight]]''\n| Rose Walker\n| Direct-to-video\n|-\n* ''[[Fateful Findings]]'' (2012) - Woman s