{"title_page": "The Parent Trap (film series)", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n'''''The Parent Trap''''' is a [[film series]] produced by [[Walt Disney Pictures]], originating in 1961 with [[Hayley Mills]]. She played both roles of [[The Twins (The Parent Trap)|twin sisters]] who were raised separately by divorced parents, without any knowledge of each other. They meet at a summer holiday camp, and switch places so that they can each meet their other parent. Mills reprised her roles three times in subsequent [[Television film|made-for-television]] sequels. \n\nA [[The Parent Trap (1998 film)|remake]] was released in 1998, with a plot similar to the original film and written by the original film's writer/director [[David Swift (director)|David Swift]], with segments of the story being reworked into a [[Romance film|romantic]]-[[Comedy film|comedy]]. The twins were portrayed by [[Lindsay Lohan]].\n\n==Films==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Occupation\n! colspan=\"6\" | Film\n|-\n! ''[[The Parent Trap (1961 film)|The Parent Trap]]''<br>(1961)\n! ''[[The Parent Trap II]]''<br>(1986)\n! ''[[Parent Trap III]]''<br>(1989)\n! ''[[Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon]]''<br>(1989)\n! ''[[The Parent Trap (1998 film)|The Parent Trap]]''<br>(1998)\n|-\n! Director\n| [[David Swift (director)|David Swift]]\n| [[Ronald F. Maxwell]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | Mollie Miller\n| [[Nancy Meyers]]\n|-\n! Producer(s)\n| [[Walt Disney]]<br>George Golitzen\n| Joan Barnett\n| Jill Donner<br>Henry Colman\n| Charles Milhaupt<br>Richard Luke Rothschild\n| [[Charles Shyer]]\n|-\n! Writer(s)\n| David Swift\n| Stuart Krieger\n| '''Screenplay by'''<br>Jill Donner<br>'''Story by'''<br>Deborah Amelon<br>Jill Donner\n| [[John McNamara (writer)|John McNamara]]\n| David Swift<br>Nancy Meyers<br>Charles Shyer\n|-\n! Composer(s)\n| [[Paul Smith (composer)|Paul Smith]]\n| [[Charles Fox (composer)|Charles Fox]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Joel McNeely]]\n| [[Alan Silvestri]]\n|-\n! Cinematographer\n| [[Lucien Ballard]]\n| [[Peter Stein (cinematographer)|Peter Stein]]\n| [[Isidore Mankofsky]]\n| [[Michel Hugo]]\n| [[Dean Cundey]]\n|-\n! Editor(s)\n| [[Philip W. Anderson (film editor)|Philip W. Anderson]]\n| [[Corky Ehlers]]\n| Howard Kunin<br>Duane Hartzell\n| Art Stafford<br>Karen I. Stern\n| [[Stephen A. Rotter]]\n|-\n! Production company\n| [[Walt Disney Pictures|Walt Disney Productions]]\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Walt Disney Television]]\n| [[Walt Disney Pictures]]\n|-\n! Distribution\n| [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Distribution]]\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television|Buena Vista Television]]\n| [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Pictures Distribution]]\n|-\n! Running time\n| 128 minutes\n| 81 minutes\n| 85 minutes\n| 86 minutes\n| 128 minutes\n|-\n! Release date\n| June 21, 1961\n| July 26, 1986\n| April 9, 1989\n| November 19, 1989\n| July 29, 1998\n|}\n\n===''The Parent Trap'' (1961)===\n{{Main|The Parent Trap (1961 film)}}\n''The Parent Trap'' was written and directed by [[David Swift (director)|David Swift]] for [[Walt Disney Pictures]] released in 1961. It was based on the book ''[[Lottie and Lisa|Das Doppelte Lottchen]]'' written by [[Erich K\u00e4stner]]. The film stars [[Hayley Mills]] who plays the roles of the thirteen-year-old twin girls, Sharon and Susan. [[Maureen O'Hara]] and [[Brian Keith]] play the twins\u2019 parents, Maggie and Mitch. The film is about the two girls who meet at a summer camp as strangers and realize that they are identical twins. They switch places so that each can meet the other parent, and they plan to bring their divorced parents back together. Soon after switching, the twins learn that there is a new woman, named Vicky Robinson (played by [[Joanna Barnes]]), in their father's life. After Mitch tells Sharon about his engagement to Vicky, the girls come up with a new game plan to get rid of the woman who threatens their plan to reconnect their parents.<ref>''The Parent Trap.'' Dir. David Swift. Perf. Hayley Mills, Maureen O\u2019Hara, and Brian Keith. Walt Disney, 1961. Film.</ref>\n\n===''The Parent Trap II'' (1986)===\n{{Main|The Parent Trap II}}\n''The Parent Trap II'', written by Stuart Krieger, is a made-for-television film that aired on July 26, 1986 on the [[Disney Channel]]. It was directed by [[Ronald F. Maxwell]]. The film is a continuation of the Walt Disney film ''The Parent Trap''. ''The Parent Trap II'' was filmed twenty-five years after the original film. The idea of a second film was announced in 1985. The only actor who returned from the original film, Hayley Mills, continues to portray the twins, Sharon and Susan. ''The Parent Trap II'' focuses on Sharon's daughter Nikki who tries to set up her mother with her best friend's father, portrayed by [[Tom Skerritt]]. All the music was composed by [[Charles Fox (composer)|Charles Fox]] as well as the title song \"Lets Keep What We Got\" was performed by [[Marilyn McCoo]].\n\n===''Parent Trap III'' (1989)===\n\n{{Main|Parent Trap III}}\n''The Parent Trap II'' was such a success for the Disney Channel that it spawned another made-for-television sequel, ''Parent Trap III'', in 1989. Hayley Mills again reprises her roles as twins Sharon and Susan, with [[Barry Bostwick]] as a father of triplet girls and [[Patricia Richardson]] as his snobbish girlfriend.\n\n===''Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon'' (1989)===\n{{Main|Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon}}\n''Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon'' (1989) is the final made-for-television sequel, with Hayley Mills again reprising her roles as Sharon and Susan, now both remarried. Also returning from ''Parent Trap III'' is Barry Bostwick and the Creel triplets: Joy, [[Leanna Creel|Leanna]] and [[Monica Lacy|Monica]].\n\n===''The Parent Trap'' (1998)===\n\n{{Main|The Parent Trap (1998 film)}}\n[[Lindsay Lohan]] stars in the remake of the original ''Parent Trap'' film, playing the role of the identical twins whose lives change at the summer camp they attend. The remake caught the attention of audiences when it premiered on July 29, 1998. The parents of the twins, Nick Parker (played by [[Dennis Quaid]]) and Elizabeth James (played by [[Natasha Richardson]]), marry on a cruise ship and quickly figure out their lives are in two separate places. They each take one of the twins and then go their separate ways. Eleven years pass and the identical twins, Annie James and Hallie Parker, embark on their summer journeys not knowing each other. The initial rivalry between them turns out to bring them closer and they realize that they must be sisters. Their new goal is to make their parents fall in love again before their father and his fianc\u00e9 Meredeth Blake (played by [[Elaine Hendrix]]) marry. The film was directed by [[Nancy Meyers]].\n\n===Potential remake===\nOn February 8, 2018, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' revealed that remakes of several live-action films are in development as exclusive content for [[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney Studios]]' upcoming streaming service [[Disney+]]; with one of those named in the announcement being ''The Parent Trap''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/disney-planning-muppets-reboot-streaming-service-1086800 |title=Disney Planning Another 'Muppets' Reboot for Its Streaming Service (Exclusive) |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=February 21, 2018 |accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Documentary on the film series==\n\n\nFamily Films Productions is developing ''The Legacy of The Parent Trap'', a documentary film that gives a retrospective insight into developing ''The Parent Trap''. <ref>http://www.familyfilmsproductions.com</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hWzPemw75M8|title=The Legacy of The Parent Trap - Official Film Trailer |first=|last=FamilyFilmsProductions.com|date=23 June 2018|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> The film will reportedly feature memories and stories of various cast and crew, about the original 1961 film and its three sequels. Among the interviews, all-new footage featuring Hayley Mills will be included. Additional interviewees include Tom Skerritt, Carrie Kei Heim, Creel triplets including, Monica Creel Lacy, Leanna & Joy Creel, Susan Henning, Ron Maxwell (Director of ''Parent Trap II'', Mollie Miller (Director of ''Parent Trap III''/''Hawaiian Honeymoon''), Tommy Sands, and Joanna Barnes and even Lynette Winters, and Kay Cole (camp inch scenes). [[Bridgette Andersen]]'s Teresa mother discusses reflections on experiences that occurred on-set during filming of ''The Parent Trap II'', with director Ron Maxwell, among others. Marilyn McCoo also is featured sharing memories about recording music for ''Parent Trap II''. Charles Fox who wrote the theme, \"Let's Get What We Got\" that was the title music in the opening for \"The Parent Trap II\", and the entire music score. He is also featured on-camera, with talking about his experiences in the music.  \n\nThe project will analyze and also focus on the life of Erich Kastner who wrote the original German book, ''[[Lottie and Lisa|Das Doppelte Lottchen]]''  that the films were based on. Luke Springman, German professor Aaron Pacentine will executive produce the film. This is the first full-length film documentary that details coverage on the 1980s Parent Trap films, and the first time the director, Mollie Miller, has spoken out publicly about the original film since then.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Lottie and Lisa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parent Trap (film series), The}}\n[[Category:The Parent Trap films| ]]\n[[Category:Comedy film series]]\n[[Category:Children's film series]]\n[[Category:Films about twin sisters]]\n[[Category:Disney film series]]\n[[Category:Film series introduced in 1961]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n'''''The Parent Trap''''' is a [[film series]] produced by [[Walt Disney Pictures]], originating in 1961 with [[Hayley Mills]]. She played both roles of [[The Twins (The Parent Trap)|twin sisters]] who were raised separately by divorced parents, without any knowledge of each other. They meet at a summer holiday camp, and switch places so that they can each meet their other parent. Mills reprised her roles three times in subsequent [[Television film|made-for-television]] sequels. \n\nA [[The Parent Trap (1998 film)|remake]] was released in 1998, with a plot similar to the original film and written by the original film's writer/director [[David Swift (director)|David Swift]], with segments of the story being reworked into a [[Romance film|romantic]]-[[Comedy film|comedy]]. The twins were portrayed by [[Lindsay Lohan]].\n\n==Films==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Occupation\n! colspan=\"6\" | Film\n|-\n! ''[[The Parent Trap (1961 film)|The Parent Trap]]''<br>(1961)\n! ''[[The Parent Trap II]]''<br>(1986)\n! ''[[Parent Trap III]]''<br>(1989)\n! ''[[Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon]]''<br>(1989)\n! ''[[The Parent Trap (1998 film)|The Parent Trap]]''<br>(1998)\n|-\n! Director\n| [[David Swift (director)|David Swift]]\n| [[Ronald F. Maxwell]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | Mollie Miller\n| [[Nancy Meyers]]\n|-\n! Producer(s)\n| [[Walt Disney]]<br>George Golitzen\n| Joan Barnett\n| Jill Donner<br>Henry Colman\n| Charles Milhaupt<br>Richard Luke Rothschild\n| [[Charles Shyer]]\n|-\n! Writer(s)\n| David Swift\n| Stuart Krieger\n| Jill Donner<br>'''Story by'''<br>Deborah Amelon<br>Jill Donner\n| [[John McNamara (writer)|John McNamara]]\n| David Swift<br>Nancy Meyers<br>Charles Shyer\n|-\n! Composer(s)\n| [[Paul Smith (composer)|Paul Smith]]\n| [[Charles Fox (composer)|Charles Fox]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | [[Joel McNeely]]\n| [[Alan Silvestri]]\n|-\n! Cinematographer\n| [[Lucien Ballard]]\n| [[Peter Stein (cinematographer)|Peter Stein]]\n| [[Isidore Mankofsky]]\n| [[Michel Hugo]]\n| [[Dean Cundey]]\n|-\n! Editor(s)\n| [[Philip W. Anderson (film editor)|Philip W. Anderson]]\n| [[Corky Ehlers]]\n| Howard Kunin<br>Duane Hartzell\n| Art Stafford<br>Karen I. Stern\n| [[Stephen A. Rotter]]\n|-\n! Production company\n| [[Walt Disney Pictures|Walt Disney Productions]]\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Walt Disney Television]]\n| [[Walt Disney Pictures]]\n|-\n! Distribution\n| [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Distribution]]\n| colspan=\"3\" | [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television|Buena Vista Television]]\n| [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Pictures Distribution]]\n|-\n! Running time\n| 128 minutes\n| 81 minutes\n| 85 minutes\n| 86 minutes\n| 128 minutes\n|-\n! Release date\n| June 21, 1961\n| July 26, 1986\n| April 9, 1989\n| November 19, 1989\n| July 29, 1998\n|}\n\n===''The Parent Trap'' (1961)===\n{{Main|The Parent Trap (1961 film)}}\n''The Parent Trap'' was written and directed by [[David Swift (director)|David Swift]] for [[Walt Disney Pictures]] released in 1961. It was based on the book ''[[Lottie and Lisa|Das Doppelte Lottchen]]'' written by [[Erich K\u00e4stner]]. The film stars [[Hayley Mills]] who plays the roles of the thirteen-year-old twin girls, Sharon and Susan. [[Maureen O'Hara]] and [[Brian Keith]] play the twins\u2019 parents, Maggie and Mitch. The film is about the two girls who meet at a summer camp as strangers and realize that they are identical twins. They switch places so that each can meet the other parent, and they plan to bring their divorced parents back together. Soon after switching, the twins learn that there is a new woman, named Vicky Robinson (played by [[Joanna Barnes]]), in their father's life. After Mitch tells Sharon about his engagement to Vicky, the girls come up with a new game plan to get rid of the woman who threatens their plan to reconnect their parents.<ref>''The Parent Trap.'' Dir. David Swift. Perf. Hayley Mills, Maureen O\u2019Hara, and Brian Keith. Walt Disney, 1961. Film.</ref>\n\n===''The Parent Trap II'' (1986)===\n{{Main|The Parent Trap II}}\n''The Parent Trap II'', written by Stuart Krieger, is a made-for-television film that aired on July 26, 1986 on the [[Disney Channel]]. It was directed by [[Ronald F. Maxwell]]. The film is a continuation of the Walt Disney film ''The Parent Trap''. ''The Parent Trap II'' was filmed twenty-five years after the original film. The idea of a second film was announced in 1985. The only actor who returned from the original film, Hayley Mills, continues to portray the twins, Sharon and Susan. ''The Parent Trap II'' focuses on Sharon's daughter Nikki who tries to set up her mother with her best friend's father, portrayed by [[Tom Skerritt]]. All the music was composed by [[Charles Fox (composer)|Charles Fox]] as well as the title song \"Lets Keep What We Got\" was performed by [[Marilyn McCoo]].\n\n===''Parent Trap III'' (1989)===\n\n{{Main|Parent Trap III}}\n''The Parent Trap II'' was such a success for the Disney Channel that it spawned another made-for-television sequel, ''Parent Trap III'', in 1989. Hayley Mills again reprises her roles as twins Sharon and Susan, with [[Barry Bostwick]] as a father of triplet girls and [[Patricia Richardson]] as his snobbish girlfriend.\n\n===''Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon'' (1989)===\n{{Main|Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon}}\n''Parent Trap: Hawaiian Honeymoon'' (1989) is the final made-for-television sequel, with Hayley Mills again reprising her roles as Sharon and Susan, now both remarried. Also returning from ''Parent Trap III'' is Barry Bostwick and the Creel triplets: Joy, [[Leanna Creel|Leanna]] and [[Monica Lacy|Monica]].\n\n===''The Parent Trap'' (1998)===\n\n{{Main|The Parent Trap (1998 film)}}\n[[Lindsay Lohan]] stars in the remake of the original ''Parent Trap'' film, playing the role of the identical twins whose lives change at the summer camp they attend. The remake caught the attention of audiences when it premiered on July 29, 1998. The parents of the twins, Nick Parker (played by [[Dennis Quaid]]) and Elizabeth James (played by [[Natasha Richardson]]), marry on a cruise ship and quickly figure out their lives are in two separate places. They each take one of the twins and then go their separate ways. Eleven years pass and the identical twins, Annie James and Hallie Parker, embark on their summer journeys not knowing each other. The initial rivalry between them turns out to bring them closer and they realize that they must be sisters. Their new goal is to make their parents fall in love again before their father and his fianc\u00e9 Meredeth Blake (played by [[Elaine Hendrix]]) marry. The film was directed by [[Nancy Meyers]].\n\n===Potential remake===\nOn February 8, 2018, ''The Hollywood Reporter'' revealed that remakes of several live-action films are in development as exclusive content for [[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney Studios]]' upcoming streaming service [[Disney+]]; with one of those named in the announcement being ''The Parent Trap''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/disney-planning-muppets-reboot-streaming-service-1086800 |title=Disney Planning Another 'Muppets' Reboot for Its Streaming Service (Exclusive) |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=February 21, 2018 |accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Documentary on the film series==\n\n\nFamily Films Productions is developing ''The Legacy of The Parent Trap'', a documentary film that gives a retrospective insight into developing ''The Parent Trap''. <ref>http://www.familyfilmsproductions.com</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hWzPemw75M8|title=The Legacy of The Parent Trap - Official Film Trailer |first=|last=FamilyFilmsProductions.com|date=23 June 2018|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> The film will reportedly feature memories and stories of various cast and crew, about the original 1961 film and its three sequels. Among the interviews, all-new footage featuring Hayley Mills will be included. Additional interviewees include Tom Skerritt, Carrie Kei Heim, Creel triplets including, Monica Creel Lacy, Leanna & Joy Creel, Susan Henning, Ron Maxwell (Director of ''Parent Trap II'', Mollie Miller (Director of ''Parent Trap III''/''Hawaiian Honeymoon''), Tommy Sands, and Joanna Barnes and even Lynette Winters, and Kay Cole (camp inch scenes). [[Bridgette Andersen]]'s Teresa mother discusses reflections on experiences that occurred on-set during filming of ''The Parent Trap II'', with director Ron Maxwell, among others. Marilyn McCoo also is featured sharing memories about recording music for ''Parent Trap II''. Charles Fox who wrote the theme, \"Let's Get What We Got\" that was the title music in the opening for \"The Parent Trap II\", and the entire music score. He is also featured on-camera, with talking about his experiences in the music.  \n\nThe project will analyze and also focus on the life of Erich Kastner who wrote the original German book, ''[[Lottie and Lisa|Das Doppelte Lottchen]]''  that the films were based on. Luke Springman, German professor Aaron Pacentine will executive produce the film. This is the first full-length film documentary that details coverage on the 1980s Parent Trap films, and the first time the director, Mollie Miller, has spoken out publicly about the original film since then.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Lottie and Lisa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parent Trap (film series), The}}\n[[Category:The Parent Trap films| ]]\n[[Category:Comedy film series]]\n[[Category:Children's film series]]\n[[Category:Films about twin sisters]]\n[[Category:Disney film series]]\n[[Category:Film series introduced in 1961]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilms", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Parent_Trap_(film_series)"}
{"title_page": "SHESHA (musician)", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=SHESHA (musician)|timestamp=20200422195023|year=2020|month=April|day=22|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=SHESHA (musician)|date=22 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{short description|Malaysian rapper, singer, songwriter, record producer}}\n{{redirect|SHESHA||Shesha (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = SHESHA\n| image            = \n| caption          = 2020\n| birth_name       = Patrick Namasivayam Seshasahi\n| alias            = {{hlist|SHESHA|Sha Zovve|Fadeproof}}\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1987|11|18}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bukit Mertajam, Penang]], Malaysia\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Rapper\n* Singer\n* Songwriter\n* Record Producer\n}}\n| years_active       = 2005\u2013present\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist <!-- See WP:WikiProject Musicians -->|embed=yes\n| background   = solo_singer<!--includes rappers-->\n| instrument   = Vocals, Synthesizer\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[pop-rap]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Electronic music]]\n}}\n| label        = {{flatlist|\n* Bimasakti Records \n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* Pistah Few\n}}\n| website = {{URL|sheshaofficial.com}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Namasivayam Seshasahi''' (born November 18, 1987), known professionally as '''SHESHA''' (stylized as '''SHESH\u0245'''), is a Malaysian rapper, singer, songwriter and record producer. \n\n==Early life==\nSHESHA was born as Patrick Namasivayam Seshasahi on 18 November 1987 in [[Bukit Mertajam]], [[Penang]], [[Malaysia]]. His mother Indera was a housewife, and his father Andrew Sivam was a store supervisor. His ancestors hailed from [[Bangalore]], [[Karnataka]] and also [[Coimbatore]], [[Madurai]], [[Tamil Nadu]]. He is the eldest of two siblings in a family consisting a sister (Patricia Sivagamy).\n\nSHESHA had his primary education at the '''Sekolah Kebangsaan Tunku Abdul Malik''' in [[Kulim]], [[Kedah]], [[Malaysia]]. As a child he had a great interest in badminton and chess. After his primary, SHESHA was enrolled at the '''Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Kulim''' . Upon completion of his school education, SHESHA performed several jobs like telemarketer, waiting staff, bartender and disc jockey while pursuing his studies in engineering in Penang. Quitting his studies in Penang, SHESHA left to Kuala Lumpur to pursue his music career. Performing several jobs like manual labour and customer service representative. Later on decided to take up sound & music course in [[Limkokwing University of Creative Technology]]. His relative and friends motivated him to join the university and supported him during this phase. SHESHA graduated with a full scholarship aid given by Tan Sri Dato\u2019 Sri Paduka Dr Limkokwing.\n\n==Career==\n===2005\u20132008===\nSHESHA under the moniker Fadeproof together with his comrades, Avathara and MC Hesh formed a band called '''Pistah Few''', influenced by the Malaysian Hip hop Group, [[Poetic Ammo]]. For two years, they ventured out as a band and serenaded local events like prom nights and cultural shows. This provided them with the opportunity to further sharpen their showmanship, emceeing skills and songwriting. Their first break rose when [[Gang Starz]], a reality television show of [[TV3 (Malaysia)|TV3]] Malaysia held its audition at Sheraton Hotel, Penang in 2007. Pistah Few was judged by Cat Farish; actor, singer and record producer and also Juliza Adzlizan; actor, singer and vocal teacher. Pistah Few\u2019s performance of self-written and composed song '''Flamethrowah''' truly awed the judges, thus enabling them to represent the northern region for the national level audition in [[Istana Budaya]], [[Kuala Lumpur]].\n\nThough they failed to proceed further, competing among groups from South East Asia provided the trio with the much needed exposure and experience to further hone musical skills and learn what\u2019s required to succeed professionally. Meeting DJ Chaoz at Gang Starz audition further led them to be introduced to the Penang Urban music scene and to perform gigs around Penang. They had the golden chances of performing at Urban Volume 2 by DJ Laze, Urban Showdown by Muneer of Urban Method along artistes like Altimet, Northsyde, Royal Maximus and many more. Soon, Pistah Few became a duo. Avathara and SHESHA continued. In 2008, Pistah Few won the competition held by ECHO PARK Penang, Hip Hop RnB Extravaganza was judged by Simon Michael (One in A Million - season 3 - finalist). In the same year, they performed for a notable charity event called 30 Hour Famine 2008 by [[World Vision International|World Vision]] Malaysia in KL. He also won the Glo Rap - Solo category competition in Penang. In 2008 too, SHESHA performed with Dareyno of Junio Hustle at Ambang Merdeka 2008 at [[Genting Highlands]], along with artistes like Ruffedge, Roshan Jamrock, [[Goldkartz]] and Henley.\n\n===2009\u20132013===\nIn the following year, he met T.A.Santhanam, a professional [[Thavil|Thavil]] player, with whom he worked on a project known as Vaanam, a tamil pop compilation album. Under the production and watchful eye of T.A.Santhanam, SHESHA worked with artists like [[M. L. R. Karthikeyan|MLR Karthikeyan]], Ganesan Manoharan ([[Astro (television)|Astro]] Vanavil Superstar Champion), Avathara (Pistah Few), M.S.V Raja (Saxophone), Kamalkhar (Woodwind), Eshwar Rao (Sitar) and many other artist. Music arrangers were Navin, a Malaysian Indian Music Industry (MIMI) Award winner and Mixing Engineer, Suresh Raaj (Chennai). SHESHA was featured for two songs in that album ; Unnai Parthe Pinbu and Vaa vaa Vasegaara. After 2 years, in 2012, Vaanam was released. . The following year ''Unnai Parthe Pinbu'' was nominated for [[Malaysian Music Awards|Anugerah Industri Muzik]] and [[VIMA Music Awards]].\n\n===2014\u20132019===\nSHESHA under the moniker Sha Zovve, produced the soundtrack ' ''Yaar Enbathey (Crazy Mix)'' ' for a tamil short film ' ''David'' ' which was in [[Raaga (radio station)|THR Raaga]] Malaysian Top 10 for 5 weeks. ''David'' was the first short film in Malaysia to distribute Callertunes for its soundtrack. He was also actively involved in film, television and music video production; ' ''Made For Each Other'' ' a [[Malayalam|Malayalam]] program made by ''Manorama TV'' [[Kerala|Kerala]], ' ''Yaali'' ' a film by [[Akshaya Rao|Akshaya Rao]], ' ''Kamalini'' ', ' ''Thedal'' ', ' ''Azhagey'' ' and more. SHESHA acted in [[Cinemax|Cinemax]] series [[Strike Back (TV series)|Strike Back]]: [[Strike Back: Revolution|Revolution]] as a insurgent, [[Radio Televisyen Malaysia|RTM]] series ' ''Dr.Love'' ' as a radio jockey. He also did lead roles in [[Public service announcement|PSA]] and short films; ' ''A Strangers Pleasure'' ', ' ''Sita'' ', ' ''The Cookbook'' '. SHESHA was nominated for [[BMW|BMW]] Shorties Best Sound Design category for ' ''The Cookbook'' '. In 2016, he produced ' ''En Jeeven Nee (ARR ANTHEM)'' ', a tribute for [[A. R. Rahman|A.R.Rahman]] Live In Concert which was held in [[Stadium Merdeka|Stadium Merdeka]], Malaysia. ' ''En Jeeven Nee'' ' was in [[Raaga (radio station)|THR Raaga]] Malaysian Top 10 for 8 weeks. Charting Number #2 in the first five weeks and Number #1 in the final three weeks. SHESHA produced signature tune for ''Malik Streams Corporation'', which was distributed  for the release of [[Theri (film)|Theri]] & [[Kabali (film)|Kabali]] film in Malaysia. He was also the Audio Engineer for [[Kabali (film)|Kabali]] [[Malay language|Malay]] version trailer release. SHESHA produced the [[Soundtrack album|Soundtrack album]] for the film ' ''Villavan-The Vigilante'' ' which was released in 2018, featuring [[Karthik (singer)|Karthik]], [[Shweta Mohan]], [[Suchith Suresan]], [[Keba Jeremiah]], [[Maria Roe Vincent]], Hyde Karty, Vassan Nassav, Avathara, Aneithazef, Meerlyn, El F\u00c9 Choir and many other artist . The soundtracks from the album was nominated for [[VIMA Music Awards]] in few categories. The following year, he produced the theme song ' ''Fabulous Lady'' ' for ''Mrs Fabulous Malaysia'' event, featuring Malaysian artist Maya Hanum.\n\n===2020\u2013present===\nIn 2020, he rebranded himself as '''SHESHA''' and started a new label, '''Bimasakti Records'''. The debut release '''Bintang EP''' is in final stage of its production, slated to release later this year.\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n;EP\n*2020: ''Bintang EP''\n\n==Awards and achievements==\n\n=== [[Malaysian Music Awards|Anugerah Industri Muzik]] ===\n\n*2013: Nominated for Best Hip Hop/Rap Song Awards for \u2018Unnai Parthe Pinbu\u2019 at the 2013 Anugerah Industri Muzik (AIM) Malaysian-Indian.<ref>https://www.aim.org.my/pdf/AIMMalaysian-Indian/AIM%20Malaysian-Indian%202013-Final%205%20List.pdf</ref>\n\n=== [[VIMA Music Awards]] ===\n\n*2013: Nominated for Best Tamil/Punjabi Song Awards for \u2018Unnai Parthe Pinbu\u2019 at the 2013 VIMA Music Awards.<ref>https://hype.my/2013/18884/vima-malaysia-final-nominees-list/</ref>\n*2013: Nominated for Best Genre-Bender Song Awards for \u2018Unnai Parthe Pinbu\u2019 at the 2013 VIMA Music Awards.\n*2018: Nominated for Best Pop Song Awards for \u2018Podu Sakka Podu\u2019 at the 2018 VIMA Music Awards.<ref>https://globalvima.com/2018/11/10/vima-2018-releases-official-nominees-list/</ref>\n*2018: Nominated for Best Indian/Punjabi Song Awards for \u2018Podu Sakka Podu\u2019 at the 2018 VIMA Music Awards.\n*2018: Nominated for Best Genre-Bender Song Awards for \u2018You Know !\u2019 at the 2018 VIMA Music Awards.\n\n=== Competitions ===\n*2006: '''[[TV3 (Malaysia)|TV3]] [[Gang Starz]]''' - '''Season 1''' ''(Top 15 Finalist)''\n*2008: '''ECHO PARK Hip Hop RnB Extravaganza''' - '''Group Category''' ''(Champion)'' \n*2008: '''GLO RAP''' - '''Solo Category''' ''(Champion)''\n*2015: '''BMW Shorties Best Sound Design Award for ''The Cookbook''.''' ''(Nominee)''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:SHESHA}}\n[[:Category:1987 births]]\n[[:Category:Living people]]\n[[:Category:Malaysian male singer-songwriters]]\n[[:Category:Malaysian hip hop singers]]\n[[:Category:Malaysian rhythm and blues singers]]\n[[:Category:Malaysian rappers]]\n[[:Category:Malay-language singers]]\n[[:Category:English-language singers from Malaysia]]\n[[:Category:Malaysian people of Indian descent]]\n[[:Category:Malaysian businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=SHESHA (musician)|timestamp=20200422195023|year=2020|month=April|day=22|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=SHESHA (musician)|date=22 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{short description|Malaysian rapper, singer, songwriter, record producer}}\n{{redirect|SHESHA||Shesha (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = SHESHA\n| image            = \n| caption          = 2020\n| birth_name       = Patrick Namasivayam Seshasahi\n| alias            = {{hlist|SHESHA|Sha Zovve|Fadeproof}}\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1987|11|18}}\n| birth_place      = [[Bukit Mertajam, Penang]], Malaysia\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Rapper\n* Singer\n* Songwriter\n* Record Producer\n}}\n| years_active       = 2005\u2013present\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist <!-- See WP:WikiProject Musicians -->|embed=yes\n| background   = solo_singer<!--includes rappers-->\n| instrument   = Vocals, Synthesizer\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[pop-rap]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Electronic music]]\n}}\n| label        = {{flatlist|\n* Bimasakti Records \n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* Pistah Few\n}}\n| website = {{URL|sheshaofficial.com}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Namasivayam Seshasahi''' (born November 18, 1987), known professionally as '''SHESHA''' (stylized as '''SHESH\u0245'''), is a Malaysian rapper, singer, songwriter and record producer. \n\n==Early life==\nSHESHA was born as Patrick Namasivayam Seshasahi on 18 November 1987 in [[Bukit Mertajam]], [[Penang]], [[Malaysia]]. His mother Indera was a housewife, and his father Andrew Sivam was a store supervisor. His ancestors hailed from [[Bangalore]], [[Karnataka]] and also [[Coimbatore]], [[Madurai]], [[Tamil Nadu]]. He is the eldest of two siblings in a family consisting a sister (Patricia Sivagamy).\n\nSHESHA had his primary education at the '''Sekolah Kebangsaan Tunku Abdul Malik''' in [[Kulim]], [[Kedah]], [[Malaysia]]. As a child he had a great interest in badminton and chess. After his primary, SHESHA was enrolled at the '''Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Kulim''' . Upon completion of his school education, SHESHA performed several jobs like telemarketer, waiting staff, bartender and disc jockey while pursuing his studies in engineering in Penang. Quitting his studies in Penang, SHESHA left to Kuala Lumpur to pursue his music career. Performing several jobs like manual labour and customer service representative. Later on decided to take up sound & music course in [[Limkokwing University of Creative Technology]]. His relative and friends motivated him to join the university and supported him during this phase. SHESHA graduated with a full scholarship aid given by Tan Sri Dato\u2019 Sri Paduka Dr Limkokwing.\n\n==Career==\n===2005\u20132008===\nSHESHA under the moniker Fadeproof together with his comrades, Avathara and MC Hesh formed a band called '''Pistah Few''', influenced by the Malaysian Hip hop Group, [[Poetic Ammo]]. For two years, they ventured out as a band and serenaded local events like prom nights and cultural shows. This provided them with the opportunity to further sharpen their showmanship, emceeing skills and songwriting. Their first break rose when [[Gang Starz]], a reality television show of [[TV3 (Malaysia)|TV3]] Malaysia held its audition at Sheraton Hotel, Penang in 2007. Pistah Few was judged by Cat Farish; actor, singer and record producer and also Juliza Adzlizan; actor, singer and vocal teacher. Pistah Few\u2019s performance of self-written and composed song '''Flamethrowah''' truly awed the judges, thus enabling them to represent the northern region for the national level audition in [[Istana Budaya]], [[Kuala Lumpur]].\n\nThough they failed to proceed further, competing among groups from South East Asia provided the trio with the much needed exposure and experience to further hone musical skills and learn what\u2019s required to succeed professionally. Meeting DJ Chaoz at Gang Starz audition further led them to be introduced to the Penang Urban music scene and to perform gigs around Penang. They had the golden chances of performing at Urban Volume 2 by DJ Laze, Urban Showdown by Muneer of Urban Method along artistes like Altimet, Northsyde, Royal Maximus and many more. Soon, Pistah Few became a duo. Avathara and SHESHA continued. In 2008, Pistah Few won the competition held by ECHO PARK Penang, Hip Hop RnB Extravaganza was judged by Simon Michael (One in A Million - season 3 - finalist). In the same year, they performed for a notable charity event called 30 Hour Famine 2008 by [[World Vision International|World Vision]] Malaysia in KL. In 2008 too, SHESHA performed with Dareyno of Junio Hustle at Ambang Merdeka 2008 at [[Genting Highlands]], along with artistes like Ruffedge, Roshan Jamrock, [[Goldkartz]] and Henley.\n\n===2009\u20132013===\nIn the following year, he met T.A.Santhanam, a professional [[Thavil|Thavil]] player, with whom he worked on a project known as Vaanam, a tamil pop compilation album. Under the production and watchful eye of T.A.Santhanam, SHESHA worked with artists like [[M. L. R. Karthikeyan|MLR Karthikeyan]], Ganesan Manoharan ([[Astro (television)|Astro]] Vanavil Superstar Champion), Avathara (Pistah Few), M.S.V Raja (Saxophone), Kamalkhar (Woodwind), Eshwar Rao (Sitar) and many other artist. Music arrangers were Navin, a Malaysian Indian Music Industry (MIMI) Award winner and Mixing Engineer, Suresh Raaj (Chennai). SHESHA was featured for two songs in that album ; Unnai Parthe Pinbu and Vaa vaa Vasegaara. After 2 years, in 2012, Vaanam was released. . The following year ''Unnai Parthe Pinbu'' was nominated for [[Malaysian Music Awards|Anugerah Industri Muzik]] and [[VIMA Music Awards]].\n\n===2014\u20132019===\nSHESHA under the moniker Sha Zovve, produced the soundtrack ' ''Yaar Enbathey (Crazy Mix)'' ' for a tamil short film ' ''David'' ' which was in [[Raaga (radio station)|THR Raaga]] Malaysian Top 10 for 5 weeks. ''David'' was the first short film in Malaysia to distribute Callertunes for its soundtrack. He was also actively involved in film, television and music video production; ' ''Made For Each Other'' ' a [[Malayalam|Malayalam]] program made by ''Manorama TV'' [[Kerala|Kerala]], ' ''Yaali'' ' a film by [[Akshaya Rao|Akshaya Rao]], ' ''Kamalini'' ', ' ''Thedal'' ', ' ''Azhagey'' ' and more. SHESHA acted in [[Cinemax|Cinemax]] series [[Strike Back (TV series)|Strike Back]]: [[Strike Back: Revolution|Revolution]] as a insurgent, [[Radio Televisyen Malaysia|RTM]] series ' ''Dr.Love'' ' as a radio jockey. He also did lead roles in [[Public service announcement|PSA]] and short films; ' ''A Strangers Pleasure'' ', ' ''Sita'' ', ' ''The Cookbook'' '. SHESHA was nominated for [[BMW|BMW]] Shorties Best Sound Design category for ' ''The Cookbook'' '. In 2016, he produced ' ''En Jeeven Nee (ARR ANTHEM)'' ', a tribute for [[A. R. Rahman|A.R.Rahman]] Live In Concert which was held in [[Stadium Merdeka|Stadium Merdeka]], Malaysia. ' ''En Jeeven Nee'' ' was in [[Raaga (radio station)|THR Raaga]] Malaysian Top 10 for 8 weeks. Charting Number #2 in the first five weeks and Number #1 in the final three weeks. SHESHA produced signature tune for ''Malik Streams Corporation'', which was distributed  for the release of [[Theri (film)|Theri]] & [[Kabali (film)|Kabali]] film in Malaysia. He was also the Audio Engineer for [[Kabali (film)|Kabali]] [[Malay language|Malay]] version trailer release. SHESHA produced the [[Soundtrack album|Soundtrack album]] for the film ' ''Villavan-The Vigilante'' ' which was released in 2018, featuring [[Karthik (singer)|Karthik]], [[Shweta Mohan]], [[Suchith Suresan]], [[Keba Jeremiah]], [[Maria Roe Vincent]], Hyde Karty, Vassan Nassav, Avathara, Aneithazef, Meerlyn, El F\u00c9 Choir and many other artist . The soundtracks from the album was nominated for [[VIMA Music Awards]] in few categories. The following year, he produced the theme song ' ''Fabulous Lady'' ' for ''Mrs Fabulous Malaysia'' event, featuring Malaysian artist Maya Hanum.\n\n===2020\u2013present===\nIn 2020, he rebranded himself as '''SHESHA''' and started a new label, '''Bimasakti Records'''. The debut release '''Bintang EP''' is in final stage of its production, slated to release later this year.\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n;EP\n*2020: ''Bintang EP''\n\n==Awards and achievements==\n\n=== [[Malaysian Music Awards|Anugerah Industri Muzik]] ===\n\n*2013: Nominated for Best Hip Hop/Rap Song Awards for \u2018Unnai Parthe Pinbu\u2019 at the 2013 Anugerah Industri Muzik (AIM) Malaysian-Indian.<ref>https://www.aim.org.my/pdf/AIMMalaysian-Indian/AIM%20Malaysian-Indian%202013-Final%205%20List.pdf</ref>\n\n=== [[VIMA Music Awards]] ===\n\n*2013: Nominated for Best Tamil/Punjabi Song Awards for \u2018Unnai Parthe Pinbu\u2019 at the 2013 VIMA Music Awards.<ref>https://hype.my/2013/18884/vima-malaysia-final-nominees-list/</ref>\n*2013: Nominated for Best Genre-Bender Song Awards for \u2018Unnai Parthe Pinbu\u2019 at the 2013 VIMA Music Awards.\n*2018: Nominated for Best Pop Song Awards for \u2018Podu Sakka Podu\u2019 at the 2018 VIMA Music Awards.<ref>https://globalvima.com/2018/11/10/vima-2018-releases-official-nominees-list/</ref>\n*2018: Nominated for Best Indian/Punjabi Song Awards for \u2018Podu Sakka Podu\u2019 at the 2018 VIMA Music Awards.\n*2018: Nominated for Best Genre-Bender Song Awards for \u2018You Know !\u2019 at the 2018 VIMA Music Awards.\n\n=== Competitions ===\n*2006: '''[[TV3 (Malaysia)|TV3]] [[Gang Starz]]''' - '''Season 1''' ''(Top 15 Finalist)''\n*2008: '''ECHO PARK Hip Hop RnB Extravaganza''' - '''Group Category''' ''(Champion)'' \n*2008: '''GLO RAP''' - '''Solo Category''' ''(Champion)''\n*2015: '''BMW Shorties Best Sound Design Award for ''The Cookbook''.''' ''(Nominee)''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:SHESHA}}\n[[:Category:1987 births]]\n[[:Category:Living people]]\n[[:Category:Malaysian male singer-songwriters]]\n[[:Category:Malaysian hip hop singers]]\n[[:Category:Malaysian rhythm and blues singers]]\n[[:Category:Malaysian rappers]]\n[[:Category:Malay-language singers]]\n[[:Category:English-language singers from Malaysia]]\n[[:Category:Malaysian people of Indian descent]]\n[[:Category:Malaysian businesspeople]]\n", "name_user": "Sarveshvara99", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2005\u20132008", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHESHA_(musician)"}
{"title_page": "Erika (given name)", "text_new": "{{Infobox given name\n| name = Erika, Erica\n| image=\n| imagesize=\n| caption=\n| pronunciation={{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u025br|\u026a|k|\u0259}}<br>{{IPA-it|\u02c8erika|lang}}<br>{{IPA-de|\u02c8e\u02d0\u0281i\u02d0ka|lang}}\n| gender = Female\n| meaning = \u201ceternal ruler\",<br>\"ever powerful\"\n| region =  \n| origin = [[Old Norse]]\n| related names = [[Eric]], [[Erik]]\n| footnotes = \n| wikt  = {{wiktionary|Erica|Erika|erica}}\n}}\nThe [[given name]] '''Erika''', '''Erica''', or '''Ericka''', is a feminine form of [[Eric]], deriving from the [[Old Norse]] name ''Eir\u00edkr'' (or ''Er\u00edkr'' in Eastern Scandinavia due to monophthongization). The first element, ''ei-'' is derived either from the older [[Proto-Norse]] ''*aina(z)'', meaning \"one, alone, unique\",<ref>Entries \"\u00c6ir\u00edk\u0280\", \"\u00c6i-\", in: [http://www.sprakochfolkminnen.se/om-oss/arkiv-och-samlingar/nordiskt-runnamnslexikon.html ''Nordiskt runnamnslexikon''] (2002) by Lena Peterson at the Swedish Institute for Linguistics and Heritage (Institutet f\u00f6r spr\u00e5k och folkminnen). [https://www.nordicnames.de/wiki/EIN Entry \"EIN\"] at ''Nordic Names''. Retrieved 19 June 2017.</ref> as in the form ''\u00c6inrikr'' explicitly, or from ''*aiwa(z)'' \"long time, eternity\".<ref>[http://www.nordicnames.de/wiki/Erik Entry \"Erik\"] at ''Nordic Names Wiki''. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref> The second element ''-r\u00edkr'' stems either from ''*r\u00edks'' \"king, ruler\" (cf. Gothic ''reiks'') or from the therefrom derived ''*r\u00edkijaz'' \"kingly, powerful, rich\".<ref>Entries \"\u00c6ir\u00edk\u0280\", \"R\u00edk\u0280\" and \"-r\u00edk\u0280\" in [http://www.sprakochfolkminnen.se/om-oss/arkiv-och-samlingar/nordiskt-runnamnslexikon.html ''Nordiskt runnamnslexikon''] (2002) by Lena Peterson at the Swedish Institute for Linguistics and Heritage (Institutet f\u00f6r spr\u00e5k och folkminnen).</ref> The name is thus usually taken to mean \"sole ruler, [[monarchy|monarch]]\" or \"eternal ruler, ever powerful\".<ref>{{cite book|title=The Study of Names: A Guide to the Principles and Topics|year=1992|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport, CT|page=11|url=https://www.questia.com/read/15138768/the-study-of-names-a-guide-to-the-principles-and|author=Frank Nuessel|accessdate=11 September 2013}} {{Subscription required|via=Questia}}</ref>\n\nIt is a common name in many [[Western world|Western societies]]. It is also a popular given name for women in [[Japan]] (even though its origin has nothing in common with the Nordic roots of the Western version). ''[[Erica]]'' is also the name of a [[genus]] of approximately 860 species of flowering plants in the family [[Ericaceae]], commonly known as \"heaths\" or \"heathers\" in English, and is the Latin word for \"heather\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Manning |first=John |author2=Paterson-Jones, Colin |title=Field Guide to Fynbos |year=2007 |page=224 |publisher=Struik Publishers, Cape Town |isbn=978-1-77007-265-7}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC right}}\n\n== People with the name ==\n*[[\u00c9rika Alcocer Luna]] (born 1974), Mexican singer, winner of the second generation of ''La Academia''\n*[[Erika Alexander]] (born 1969), American actress\n*[[Erica Alfridi]] (born 1968), Italian race walker\n*[[Erika Araki]] (born 1984), Japanese national volleyball team captain\n*[[Erica Atkins-Campbell]], (born 1972), American singer most famous from Mary Mary\n*[[Erica Bartolina]] (born 1980), American pole vaulter\n*[[Erica Bougard]] (born 1993), American heptathlete\n*[[Erika von Brockdorff]] (1911\u20131943), German resistance fighter during the Second World War\n*[[Erika Christensen]] (born 1982), American actress\n*[[Erika Coimbra]] (born 1980), Brazilian volleyball player\n*[[Erika Cosby]], American painter and daughter of Bill Cosby\n*[[Erika Costell]] (born 1993), American YouTuber, model, and singer\n*[[Erika Cremer]] (1900\u20131996), German physicist\n*[[Erica Durance]] (born 1978), Canadian actress\n*[[Erika Eleniak]] (born 1969), American actress and Playboy Playmate\n*[[Erika Ender]] (born 1974), Panamanian singer, songwriter and actress\n*[[Erika Fisch]] (born 1934), German athlete\n*[[Erika Fuchs]] (1906\u20132005), German translator\n*[[Erica Garner]] (1990-2017), American activist\n*[[Erika Gonz\u00e1lez]] (born 1972), Mexican freestyle swimmer\n*[[Erika Hansen]] (born 1970), American swimmer\n*[[Erika Hamden]], US astrophysicist and Assistant Professor\n*[[Erika Heynatz]] (1975-), Australian model, actress, singer and television personality\n*[[Erica Jarder]] (born 1986), Swedish long jumper\n*[[Erica Hill]] (born 1976), American journalist\n*[[Erika Jayne]], dance/electronica artist\n*[[Erica Johansson]] (born 1974), Swedish long jumper\n*[[Erica Jong]] (born 1942), American author\n*[[Erika Kaljusaar]] (born 1956), Estonian actress\n*[[Erika Kinsey]] (born 1988), Swedish high jumper\n*[[Erika Kirpu]] (born 1992), Estonian \u00e9p\u00e9e fencer\n*[[Erika Landin]], actress and ''Big Brother'' contestant\n*[[Erika Liebman]] (1738\u20131803), Swedish poet\n*[[Erika deLone]], (born 1972), retired American professional tennis player\n*[[Erica Luttrell]] (born 1982), Canadian actress\n*Erica Mahoney]] (born 1972) aspiring actress, small biz owner, and mother to famous Izzie Mahoney\n*[[Erika Mann]] (1905\u20131969), German writer, the daughter of Thomas Mann\n*[[Erika Mann (politician)]] (born 1950), German politician\n*[[Erika Mar\u00edn-Spiotta]], Spanish-born biogeochemist and ecosystem ecologist\n*''Erika Mitchell'' is the real name of author [[E. L. James]] (born 1963)\n*[[Erika Nara]], Japanese Paralympic swimmer\n*[[\u00c9rika Olivera]] (born 1976), Chilean marathon runner\n*[[Erica Packer]] (born 1975), Australian singer and model\n*[[Erica Parsons]] (1998-2011), American child abuse and murder victim\n*[[Erika Pluhar]] (born 1939), Austrian actress, singer and author\n*[[Erica Rose]] (born 1982), American long-distance swimmer\n*[[Erika Rudolf]] (born 1954), Hungarian high jumper\n*[[Erica Sakurazawa]] (born 1963), Japanese manga author\n*[[\u00c9rika]] or \u00c9rika Cristiano dos Santos (born 1988), Brazilian football defender\n*[[Erika Sawajiri]] (\u6ca2\u5c3b \u30a8\u30ea\u30ab, born 1986), Japanese gravure model, singer and actress\n*[[Erika Slezak]] (born 1946), American actress best known for her long-running role as Viki Davidson on ''One Life to Live''\n*[[\u00c9rika de Souza]] (born 1982), Brazilian basketball player\n*[[Erika Steinbach]] (born 1943), German politician\n*[[Erika Toda]] (\u6238\u7530 \u6075\u68a8\u9999, born 1988), Japanese actress\n*[[Erika Umeda]] (born 1991), Japanese singer and model, former member of [[Cute (Japanese idol group)|Cute]]\n*[[Erika Wendt]] (1917\u20132003), German WWII spy\n*[[Erika Yazawa]] (born 1990), Japanese gravure model, actress and member of [[Idoling!!!]]\n*[[Erika Zavaleta]], American ecologist and evolutionary biologist\n* [[Erykah Badu]] (born 1971), American singer-songwriter, record producer, activist, and actress\n*Erica Harlin, Computer Science student of University of Indonesia\\\n\n== Fictional characters ==\n*Erika, the eponymous character of the German marching song \"[[Erika (song)|Erika]]\"\n*[[Erika (Pok\u00e9mon)]], a character in the video game series ''Pok\u00e9mon''\n*[[Erika (Underworld)]], a character in the film ''Underworld''\n*[[List of Medabots characters#Erika|Erika]], a character in the media franchise ''Medabots''\n*Erika, a character in the anime series ''[[T\u014dsh\u014d Daimos]]''\n*Erica Ainsworth, a character in the manga series ''[[Fate/kaleid liner Prisma Illya]]''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Aoyama|\u9752\u5c71 \u7d75\u91cc\u9999}}, a character in the anime series ''[[Anime-Gataris]]''\n*[[Erika Berger]], a character in the novel series ''Millennium''\n*{{Nihongo|[[The Irregular at Magic High School#Tatsuya's group|Erika Chiba]]|\u5343\u8449 \u30a8\u30ea\u30ab}}, a character in the light novel series ''The Irregular at Magic High School''\n*Erica Davidson, a character in the television series ''[[Prisoner (TV series)|Prisoner]]''\n*[[Erica Farrell]], a character in the media franchise ''Degrassi''\n*[[Erica Fontaine]], a character in the media franchise ''Sakura Taisen''\n*[[Erika (Friends)|Erika Ford]], a character in the television series ''Friends''\n*{{Nihongo|[[List of Umineko When They Cry characters#Other humans|Erika Furudo]]|\u53e4\u6238 \u30f1\u30ea\u30ab}}, a character in the visual novel series ''Umineko When They Cry''\n*Erica Goldberg, a character in the television series ''[[The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)|The Goldbergs]]''\n*[[Erica Hahn]], a character in the television series ''Grey's Anatomy''\n*Erica Hale, a character in [[Stuart Gibbs]]'s series ''Spy School''\n*[[Erica Hartmann]], a character in the media franchise ''Strike Witches''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Itsumi|\u9038\u898b \u30a8\u30ea\u30ab}}, a character in the anime series ''[[Girls und Panzer]]''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Kurumi|\u6765\u6d77 \u3048\u308a\u304b}}, a character in the anime series ''[[HeartCatch PreCure!]]''\n*{{Nihongo|[[List of Megatokyo characters#Hayasaka Erika|Hayasaka Erika]]|\u65e9\u5742 \u3048\u308a\u304b}}, a character in the webcomic ''Megatokyo''\n*[[Erica Kane]], a character in the soap opera ''All My Children''\n*[[Erika Kohut]], protagonist of the novel ''The Piano Teacher''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Sendo|\u5343\u5802 \u745b\u91cc\u83ef}}, a character in the visual novel ''[[Fortune Arterial]]''\n*[[List of Teen Wolf characters#Erica|Erica Reyes]], a character in the television series ''Teen Wolf''\n*[[Erica Strangfe]], a character in the television series ''Being Erica''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Shinohara|\u7be0\u539f \u30a8\u30ea\u30ab}}, a character in the manga series ''[[Wolf Girl and Black Prince]]''\n*Erika Shiragami, a character in the film ''[[Godzilla vs. Biollante]]''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Suzuki|\u9234\u6728 \u30a8\u30ea\u30ab}}, a character in the anime series ''[[Sakura Quest]]''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Takatou|\u9ad8\u9060 \u30a8\u30ea\u30ab}}, a character in the anime series ''[[Ginga e Kickoff!!]]''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Usami|\u5b87\u4f50\u7f8e \u3048\u308a\u9999}}, a character in the anime series ''[[Tsuritama]]''\n*[[Erica Yurken]], protagonist of the novel ''Hating Alison Ashley''\n*Erica, mascot of the [[Nintendo]] mobile app [[Miitomo]]\n*Erica Sinclair, sister of Lucas Sinclair in Stranger Things\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Erika (disambiguation)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{given name}}\n<!-- It does not help to add disambig or hndis tags where the page only contains people who share a given name -->\n\n[[Category:Japanese feminine given names]]\n[[Category:English-language feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Swedish feminine given names]]\n[[Category:German feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Swiss feminine given names]]\n[[Category:English feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Finnish feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Danish feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Norwegian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Icelandic feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Scandinavian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Spanish feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Portuguese feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Italian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Estonian feminine given names]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox given name\n| name = Erika, Erica\n| image=\n| imagesize=\n| caption=\n| pronunciation={{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u025br|\u026a|k|\u0259}}<br>{{IPA-it|\u02c8erika|lang}}<br>{{IPA-de|\u02c8e\u02d0\u0281i\u02d0ka|lang}}\n| gender = Female\n| meaning = \u201ceternal ruler\",<br>\"ever powerful\"\n| region =  \n| origin = [[Old Norse]]\n| related names = [[Eric]], [[Erik]]\n| footnotes = \n| wikt  = {{wiktionary|Erica|Erika|erica}}\n}}\nThe [[given name]] '''Erika''', '''Erica''', or '''Ericka''', is a feminine form of [[Eric]], deriving from the [[Old Norse]] name ''Eir\u00edkr'' (or ''Er\u00edkr'' in Eastern Scandinavia due to monophthongization). The first element, ''ei-'' is derived either from the older [[Proto-Norse]] ''*aina(z)'', meaning \"one, alone, unique\",<ref>Entries \"\u00c6ir\u00edk\u0280\", \"\u00c6i-\", in: [http://www.sprakochfolkminnen.se/om-oss/arkiv-och-samlingar/nordiskt-runnamnslexikon.html ''Nordiskt runnamnslexikon''] (2002) by Lena Peterson at the Swedish Institute for Linguistics and Heritage (Institutet f\u00f6r spr\u00e5k och folkminnen). [https://www.nordicnames.de/wiki/EIN Entry \"EIN\"] at ''Nordic Names''. Retrieved 19 June 2017.</ref> as in the form ''\u00c6inrikr'' explicitly, or from ''*aiwa(z)'' \"long time, eternity\".<ref>[http://www.nordicnames.de/wiki/Erik Entry \"Erik\"] at ''Nordic Names Wiki''. Retrieved 1 February 2013.</ref> The second element ''-r\u00edkr'' stems either from ''*r\u00edks'' \"king, ruler\" (cf. Gothic ''reiks'') or from the therefrom derived ''*r\u00edkijaz'' \"kingly, powerful, rich\".<ref>Entries \"\u00c6ir\u00edk\u0280\", \"R\u00edk\u0280\" and \"-r\u00edk\u0280\" in [http://www.sprakochfolkminnen.se/om-oss/arkiv-och-samlingar/nordiskt-runnamnslexikon.html ''Nordiskt runnamnslexikon''] (2002) by Lena Peterson at the Swedish Institute for Linguistics and Heritage (Institutet f\u00f6r spr\u00e5k och folkminnen).</ref> The name is thus usually taken to mean \"sole ruler, [[monarchy|monarch]]\" or \"eternal ruler, ever powerful\".<ref>{{cite book|title=The Study of Names: A Guide to the Principles and Topics|year=1992|publisher=Greenwood Press|location=Westport, CT|page=11|url=https://www.questia.com/read/15138768/the-study-of-names-a-guide-to-the-principles-and|author=Frank Nuessel|accessdate=11 September 2013}} {{Subscription required|via=Questia}}</ref>\n\nIt is a common name in many [[Western world|Western societies]]. It is also a popular given name for women in [[Japan]] (even though its origin has nothing in common with the Nordic roots of the Western version). ''[[Erica]]'' is also the name of a [[genus]] of approximately 860 species of flowering plants in the family [[Ericaceae]], commonly known as \"heaths\" or \"heathers\" in English, and is the Latin word for \"heather\".<ref>{{cite book |last=Manning |first=John |author2=Paterson-Jones, Colin |title=Field Guide to Fynbos |year=2007 |page=224 |publisher=Struik Publishers, Cape Town |isbn=978-1-77007-265-7}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC right}}\n\n== People with the name ==\n*[[\u00c9rika Alcocer Luna]] (born 1974), Mexican singer, winner of the second generation of ''La Academia''\n*[[Erika Alexander]] (born 1969), American actress\n*[[Erica Alfridi]] (born 1968), Italian race walker\n*[[Erika Araki]] (born 1984), Japanese national volleyball team captain\n*[[Erica Atkins-Campbell]], (born 1972), American singer most famous from Mary Mary\n*[[Erica Bartolina]] (born 1980), American pole vaulter\n*[[Erica Bougard]] (born 1993), American heptathlete\n*[[Erika von Brockdorff]] (1911\u20131943), German resistance fighter during the Second World War\n*[[Erika Christensen]] (born 1982), American actress\n*[[Erika Coimbra]] (born 1980), Brazilian volleyball player\n*[[Erika Cosby]], American painter and daughter of Bill Cosby\n*[[Erika Costell]] (born 1993), American YouTuber, model, and singer\n*[[Erika Cremer]] (1900\u20131996), German physicist\n*[[Erica Durance]] (born 1978), Canadian actress\n*[[Erika Eleniak]] (born 1969), American actress and Playboy Playmate\n*[[Erika Ender]] (born 1974), Panamanian singer, songwriter and actress\n*[[Erika Fisch]] (born 1934), German athlete\n*[[Erika Fuchs]] (1906\u20132005), German translator\n*[[Erica Garner]] (1990-2017), American activist\n*[[Erika Gonz\u00e1lez]] (born 1972), Mexican freestyle swimmer\n*[[Erika Hansen]] (born 1970), American swimmer\n*[[Erika Hamden]], US astrophysicist and Assistant Professor\n*[[Erika Heynatz]] (1975-), Australian model, actress, singer and television personality\n*[[Erica Jarder]] (born 1986), Swedish long jumper\n*[[Erica Hill]] (born 1976), American journalist\n*[[Erika Jayne]], dance/electronica artist\n*[[Erica Johansson]] (born 1974), Swedish long jumper\n*[[Erica Jong]] (born 1942), American author\n*[[Erika Kaljusaar]] (born 1956), Estonian actress\n*[[Erika Kinsey]] (born 1988), Swedish high jumper\n*[[Erika Kirpu]] (born 1992), Estonian \u00e9p\u00e9e fencer\n*[[Erika Landin]], actress and ''Big Brother'' contestant\n*[[Erika Liebman]] (1738\u20131803), Swedish poet\n*[[Erika deLone]], (born 1972), retired American professional tennis player\n*[[Erica Luttrell]] (born 1982), Canadian actress\n*[[Erika Mann]] (1905\u20131969), German writer, the daughter of Thomas Mann\n*[[Erika Mann (politician)]] (born 1950), German politician\n*[[Erika Mar\u00edn-Spiotta]], Spanish-born biogeochemist and ecosystem ecologist\n*''Erika Mitchell'' is the real name of author [[E. L. James]] (born 1963)\n*[[Erika Nara]], Japanese Paralympic swimmer\n*[[\u00c9rika Olivera]] (born 1976), Chilean marathon runner\n*[[Erica Packer]] (born 1975), Australian singer and model\n*[[Erica Parsons]] (1998-2011), American child abuse and murder victim\n*[[Erika Pluhar]] (born 1939), Austrian actress, singer and author\n*[[Erica Rose]] (born 1982), American long-distance swimmer\n*[[Erika Rudolf]] (born 1954), Hungarian high jumper\n*[[Erica Sakurazawa]] (born 1963), Japanese manga author\n*[[\u00c9rika]] or \u00c9rika Cristiano dos Santos (born 1988), Brazilian football defender\n*[[Erika Sawajiri]] (\u6ca2\u5c3b \u30a8\u30ea\u30ab, born 1986), Japanese gravure model, singer and actress\n*[[Erika Slezak]] (born 1946), American actress best known for her long-running role as Viki Davidson on ''One Life to Live''\n*[[\u00c9rika de Souza]] (born 1982), Brazilian basketball player\n*[[Erika Steinbach]] (born 1943), German politician\n*[[Erika Toda]] (\u6238\u7530 \u6075\u68a8\u9999, born 1988), Japanese actress\n*[[Erika Umeda]] (born 1991), Japanese singer and model, former member of [[Cute (Japanese idol group)|Cute]]\n*[[Erika Wendt]] (1917\u20132003), German WWII spy\n*[[Erika Yazawa]] (born 1990), Japanese gravure model, actress and member of [[Idoling!!!]]\n*[[Erika Zavaleta]], American ecologist and evolutionary biologist\n* [[Erykah Badu]] (born 1971), American singer-songwriter, record producer, activist, and actress\n*Erica Harlin, Computer Science student of University of Indonesia\\\n\n== Fictional characters ==\n*Erika, the eponymous character of the German marching song \"[[Erika (song)|Erika]]\"\n*[[Erika (Pok\u00e9mon)]], a character in the video game series ''Pok\u00e9mon''\n*[[Erika (Underworld)]], a character in the film ''Underworld''\n*[[List of Medabots characters#Erika|Erika]], a character in the media franchise ''Medabots''\n*Erika, a character in the anime series ''[[T\u014dsh\u014d Daimos]]''\n*Erica Ainsworth, a character in the manga series ''[[Fate/kaleid liner Prisma Illya]]''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Aoyama|\u9752\u5c71 \u7d75\u91cc\u9999}}, a character in the anime series ''[[Anime-Gataris]]''\n*[[Erika Berger]], a character in the novel series ''Millennium''\n*{{Nihongo|[[The Irregular at Magic High School#Tatsuya's group|Erika Chiba]]|\u5343\u8449 \u30a8\u30ea\u30ab}}, a character in the light novel series ''The Irregular at Magic High School''\n*Erica Davidson, a character in the television series ''[[Prisoner (TV series)|Prisoner]]''\n*[[Erica Farrell]], a character in the media franchise ''Degrassi''\n*[[Erica Fontaine]], a character in the media franchise ''Sakura Taisen''\n*[[Erika (Friends)|Erika Ford]], a character in the television series ''Friends''\n*{{Nihongo|[[List of Umineko When They Cry characters#Other humans|Erika Furudo]]|\u53e4\u6238 \u30f1\u30ea\u30ab}}, a character in the visual novel series ''Umineko When They Cry''\n*Erica Goldberg, a character in the television series ''[[The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)|The Goldbergs]]''\n*[[Erica Hahn]], a character in the television series ''Grey's Anatomy''\n*Erica Hale, a character in [[Stuart Gibbs]]'s series ''Spy School''\n*[[Erica Hartmann]], a character in the media franchise ''Strike Witches''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Itsumi|\u9038\u898b \u30a8\u30ea\u30ab}}, a character in the anime series ''[[Girls und Panzer]]''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Kurumi|\u6765\u6d77 \u3048\u308a\u304b}}, a character in the anime series ''[[HeartCatch PreCure!]]''\n*{{Nihongo|[[List of Megatokyo characters#Hayasaka Erika|Hayasaka Erika]]|\u65e9\u5742 \u3048\u308a\u304b}}, a character in the webcomic ''Megatokyo''\n*[[Erica Kane]], a character in the soap opera ''All My Children''\n*[[Erika Kohut]], protagonist of the novel ''The Piano Teacher''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Sendo|\u5343\u5802 \u745b\u91cc\u83ef}}, a character in the visual novel ''[[Fortune Arterial]]''\n*[[List of Teen Wolf characters#Erica|Erica Reyes]], a character in the television series ''Teen Wolf''\n*[[Erica Strangfe]], a character in the television series ''Being Erica''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Shinohara|\u7be0\u539f \u30a8\u30ea\u30ab}}, a character in the manga series ''[[Wolf Girl and Black Prince]]''\n*Erika Shiragami, a character in the film ''[[Godzilla vs. Biollante]]''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Suzuki|\u9234\u6728 \u30a8\u30ea\u30ab}}, a character in the anime series ''[[Sakura Quest]]''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Takatou|\u9ad8\u9060 \u30a8\u30ea\u30ab}}, a character in the anime series ''[[Ginga e Kickoff!!]]''\n*{{Nihongo|Erika Usami|\u5b87\u4f50\u7f8e \u3048\u308a\u9999}}, a character in the anime series ''[[Tsuritama]]''\n*[[Erica Yurken]], protagonist of the novel ''Hating Alison Ashley''\n*Erica, mascot of the [[Nintendo]] mobile app [[Miitomo]]\n*Erica Sinclair, sister of Lucas Sinclair in Stranger Things\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Erika (disambiguation)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{given name}}\n<!-- It does not help to add disambig or hndis tags where the page only contains people who share a given name -->\n\n[[Category:Japanese feminine given names]]\n[[Category:English-language feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Swedish feminine given names]]\n[[Category:German feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Swiss feminine given names]]\n[[Category:English feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Finnish feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Danish feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Norwegian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Icelandic feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Scandinavian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Spanish feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Portuguese feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Italian feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Estonian feminine given names]]\n", "name_user": "Iz6vintage", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePeople with the name:Added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erika_(given_name)"}
{"title_page": "Julian Robertson", "text_new": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n{{about||the English badminton player|Julian Robertson (badminton)|the British First Sea Lord|Julian Oswald}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Julian Robertson\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Julian Hart Robertson Jr.\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1932|6|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Salisbury, North Carolina]], US\n| residence          = [[Locust Valley, New York]], U.S.\n| nationality        = American\n| alma_mater         = [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]\n| occupation         = Hedge fund manager and philanthropist\n| employer           = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|Josephine Tucker Robertson|1972|2010|reason=her death}}\n| networth           = [[US$]]4.4 billion (November 2019)<ref name=\"forbes.com\" />\n}}\n'''Julian Hart Robertson Jr.''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|KNZMh}} (born June 25, 1932)<ref>{{Cite news| url = http://www.nndb.com/people/260/000163768/|title=Julian H. Robertson Jr.|publisher=[[NNDB]] |accessdate = September 20, 2014}}</ref> is an American billionaire [[hedge fund|hedge fund manager]], and philanthropist. Now retired, Robertson invests in other hedge funds, mostly those run by former employees of his own defunct hedge fund company, [[Tiger Management]]. The so-called ''Tiger cubs'' manage around 50 of the world's top hedge funds, including Stephen Mandal's Lone Pine, Andreas Halvorsen's Viking, Rob Citrone's Discovery Capital Management, Philippe Laffont of Coatue Management, Lee Ainslie of Maverick Capital and [[Chase Coleman III|Chase Coleman]] of Tiger Global Management.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.valuewalk.com/2017/01/julian-robertson-start-management-avoid-reits/|title=Julian Robertson \u2013 Start With Management & Avoid REIT\u2019s|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He is a signatory of [[The Giving Pledge]].\n\nRobertson founded Tiger Management, one of the earliest hedge funds. Robertson is credited with turning $8 million in start-up capital in 1980 into over $22 billion in the late 1990s, though that was followed by a rapid downward spiral of investor withdrawals that ended with the fund closing in 2000.<ref>{{Cite news| url =http://money.cnn.com/2000/03/30/mutualfunds/q_funds_tiger/|title= Tiger Management closes |author= Jennifer Karchmer |publisher=[[CNNMoney]] |date =March 30, 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, his compensation and share of Tiger's gain exceeded $300 million. His 2003 estimated net worth was over $400 million, and in December 2017 it was estimated by ''[[Forbes]]'' at $4.1 billion.<ref name=\"forbes.com\">[https://www.forbes.com/profile/julian-robertson Julian Robertson - Forbes], Forbes.com. Accessed May 2015.</ref> Robertson said in 2008 that he shorted subprime securities and made money through credit default swaps.<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/2008/01/28/news/newsmakers/okeefe_tiger.fortune/index.htm Tiger's Julian Robertson Roars Again], Brian O'Keefe, ''Fortune'' Senior Editor, Jan. 28, 2008</ref> The following year, according to ''Forbes'', Robertson's return on his $200 million personal trading account was 150 percent.<ref name=\"forbes.com\"/>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRobertson is the son of Julian Hart Robertson Sr., a textile company executive, and the former Blanche Spencer.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AMlmfpPt3jwC&pg=PA20 Julian Robertson: A Tiger in the Land of Bulls and Bears], Daniel A. Strachman, Published by John Wiley and Sons, 2004, {{ISBN|0-471-32363-2}}</ref> He graduated from [[Episcopal High School (Alexandria, Virginia)|Episcopal High School]] in 1951 and the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] in 1955.  While at Chapel Hill, he was admitted to [[Zeta Psi]] fraternity.  He then served as an officer in the [[U.S. Navy]] until 1957.<ref name=\"Rowe\">Rowe.</ref>\n\nAfter leaving the Navy, Robertson moved to New York City and worked for a time as a stockbroker for [[Kidder, Peabody & Co.]] At Kidder, he eventually headed the firm's asset management division (Webster Securities) before departing to move with his family to New Zealand for a year to write a novel. On his return, in 1980 Robertson launched [[Tiger Management]] with initial investments from friends and family.<ref name=\"Rowe\"/>\n\n==Investment career==\nOn April 1, 1996, ''[[BusinessWeek]]'' carried a cover story written by reporter [[Gary Weiss]], called \"Fall of the Wizard\", that was critical of Robertson's performance and behavior as founder and manager of Tiger Management.  Robertson subsequently sued Weiss and ''BusinessWeek'' for $1 billion for [[defamation]].  The suit was [[Settlement (litigation)|settled]] with no money changing hands and ''BusinessWeek'' standing by the substance of its reporting.<ref>\n*{{cite news |url= |title= Digital, corner newsstands go head-to-head:  Question of timing in magazine publishing goes to court |work= [[The Fresno Bee]] |first= |last= [[Associated Press]] |publisher= |page= D14  |date=November 4, 1997}}\n*{{cite news|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-19460270 |title=Steep libel claims raise concerns |work=Folio:  The Magazine for Magazine Management |first=Jeff |last=Garigliano |publisher=[[Cowles Media Company|Cowles Business Media Inc.]] |page=19 |date=June 1, 1997 }}\n*{{cite news |url= |title= Money Aside, Manager Settles Suit |work= [[New York Daily News]] |first= Keith J. |last= Kelly |publisher= |page= 78  |date=December 18, 1997}}\n*{{cite news |url= |title= Corrections  |work=[[New York Times]] |publisher= |date= January 7, 1997}}\n*{{cite news |url= |title= Investor files papers signaling intent to sue Business Week for $1 billion |work= [[Wall Street Journal]] |first= Patrick M. |last= Reilly |publisher= [[Dow Jones & Company|Dow Jones]]   |date=April 4, 1997}}\n*{{cite news |url= |title= Business Week Agrees to Settle Libel Suit Brought by Investor  |work=[[Wall Street Journal]] |publisher= [[Dow Jones & Company|Dow Jones]] |date=December 18, 1997}}\n*{{cite news\n |last=Pogrebin \n |first=Robin \n |date=November 3, 1997 \n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/03/business/publication-date-open-to-dispute-in-internet-age.html?scp=1&sq=Publication%20Date%20Open%20to%20Dispute%20In%20Internet%20Age&st=cse \n |title=Publication Date Open to Dispute In Internet Age \n |format=Newspaper article \n |work=[[New York Times]] \n |publisher= \n |accessdate=November 11, 2009 \n}}\n*{{cite news\n |last=Truell \n |first=Peter \n |date=December 18, 1997 \n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/18/business/the-media-business-investor-settles-libel-suit-against-business-week.html?scp=1&sq=Investor%20Settles%20Libel%20Suit%20Against%20Business%20Week&st=cse \n |title=The Media Business;  Investor Settles Libel Suit Against Business Week \n |format=Newspaper article \n |work=[[New York Times]] \n |publisher= \n |accessdate=November 11, 2009 \n}}\n*{{cite web\n |last=Weiss \n |first=Gary \n |date=April 1, 1996 \n |url=http://www.businessweek.com/1996/14/b34692.htm \n |title=Fall of the Wizard \n |format=Magazine article \n |work=[[Business Week]] \n |publisher=[[McGraw-Hill]] \n |accessdate=November 11, 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216034434/http://www.businessweek.com/1996/14/b34692.htm \n |archivedate=December 16, 2009 \n}}</ref>\n\nThe Tiger funds reached a peak of $22 billion in assets in 1998. Robertson's Tiger Fund accurately predicted the [[Tech Bubble]], purposely underweighting the sector due to the overpricing of technology securities in comparison to their earnings and earning potential. So, though Tiger underperformed the S&P 500 in the short term, the fund accurately predicted the underlying flaw in the market. \"The proportion invested into technology stocks by Tiger Management, for example, a well-known value-manager, is low. In 1999 Tiger eliminated virtually all investments in this segment. This is consistent with the widely reported refusal of Julian Robertson, manager of the Tiger Fund, to buy into the internet bubble.\"<ref name=\"investopedia_2015\">{{citation |author=Loth, Richard |url=http://www.investopedia.com/university/greatest/julianrobertson.asp |title=The Greatest Investors: Julian Robertson |work=[[Investopedia]] |accessdate=2015-11-19 }}</ref>\n\nTiger's largest equity holding at that time was [[U.S. Airways]], whose troubles dragged down the value of his holdings. Such missteps ultimately led him to close his investment company in March 2000 and return all outside capital to investors. Tiger earlier made $2 billion in gains but then gave most of them back during a huge one-day move in the yen in 1998. In September 2001, Robertson distributed 24.8 million greatly devalued U.S. Airways shares to former Tiger investors. Robertson declared his intent to hold onto his own stock in the airline.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/23/business/investing-diary-left-holding-the-bag-on-us-airways-stock.html \"Investing Diary; Left Holding the Bag On US Airways Stock\"], by Laurence Zuckerman, September 23, 2001</ref>\n\n==After Tiger==\n[[File:Flickr - RalphJB - Kauri Cliffs Lodge (6).jpg|thumb|Kauri Cliffs Lodge near [[Matauri Bay]]]]\nAfter closing his fund in 2000, Robertson kept his hand in the hedge fund business by supporting and financing upcoming hedge fund managers (38 in total as of September 2009), in return for a stake in their fund  management companies. Apart from those, many of the analysts and managers Robertson employed and mentored at Tiger Management, including Chris Shumway, [[Lee Ainslie]] and [[Ole Andreas Halvorsen]] went out on their own and are now running some of the best-known hedge fund firms, called \"Tiger Cubs\".<ref>[http://www.opalesque.com/tiger - list of 38 Tiger Seeds and 32 Tiger Cubs]</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2012/07/30/business/The-Tiger-and-His-Cubs.html \"The Tiger and His Cubs,\"] New York Times, July 30, 2012</ref> These include funds such as [[Viking Global Investors]], Tiger Legatus, Tiger Veda, [[Blue Ridge Capital]], JAT Capital Management, Tiger Global, [[Maverick Capital]], [[Coatue Management]], Nehal Chopra's Tiger Ratan Capital Fund NA<ref>Copeland, Rob, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/hedge-fund-prodigy-takes-a-300-million-hit-1447027806 \"Hedge-Fund Prodigy Takes a $300 Million Hit\"], Wall Street ''Journal'', November 8, 2015. Earlier in 2015, Chopra became 'one of the few women to manage more than $1 billion in an industry long dominated by men'. Retrieved 2015-11-09.</ref><ref>Vardi, Nathan, [https://www.forbes.com/sites/nathanvardi/2015/07/24/nehal-chopra-runs-circles-around-the-boys-with-top-performing-hedge-fund/ \"Nehal Chopra Runs Circles Around The Boys With Top Performing Hedge Fund\"], ''Forbes'', July 24, 2015. Retrieved 2015-11-09.</ref> among others.\n\nRobertson is the founder and benefactor of the [[Robertson Scholars Program]] which awards a merit scholarship that provides four-year full-tuition, room, and board, and travel funding for 36 [[Duke University]] and [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] students each year.\n\nIn August 2010, Robertson signed [[The Giving Pledge]], an initiative by software mogul [[Bill Gates]] and investor [[Warren Buffett]] in which the wealthy would pledge at least half their assets to charity.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2010/aug/04/us-billionaires-half-fortune-gates |title=US billionaires club together \u2013 to give away half their fortunes to good causes |work=The Guardian |date=4 August 2010 | location=London | first=Andrew | last=Clark}}</ref>\n\nHe also is active as an investor and developer in [[New Zealand]], where he spends some time. His family owns three lodges: Kauri Cliffs Lodge near [[Matauri Bay]] in [[Northland Region|Northland]]; Matakauri Lodge [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]]; and The Farm at [[Cape Kidnappers]], [[Hawke's Bay region|Hawkes Bay]], as well as several wineries. Robertson was appointed an [[New Zealand Order of Merit|Honorary Knight Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]], for services to business and philanthropy, in the [[2010 New Year Honours (New Zealand)|2010 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10617907 |title=New Year Honours: Full 2010 list |work=The New Zealand Herald |date=31 December 2009 }}</ref> In 2009, it was announced that Robertson would donate art valued at $115 million to the [[Auckland Art Gallery Toi o T\u0101maki|Auckland Art Gallery]]. The donation included works by [[Paul Cezanne]], [[Paul Gauguin]], [[Pablo Picasso]], [[Henri Matisse]], [[Piet Mondrian]], [[Salvador Dali]], [[Georges Braque]], [[Andre Derain]], [[Fernand Leger]], [[Pierre Bonnard]] and [[Henri Fantin-Latour]] and was the largest of its kind in Australasia.<ref name=nzdonation>{{cite news |last=Herrick|first=Linda |date=9 February 2009 |title=Picassos among $115m gift to Auckland |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10571094 |work=NZ Herald |location= |access-date=15 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2010 the [[New York Stem Cell Foundation]], a private research institution, received a $27 million gift from Robertson to fund its research.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704635204575242444135532502?KEYWORDS=josie+robertson Hedge-Fund Founder Bolsters Stem-Cell Research with $27 million Gift],'' The Wall Street Journal'', 14 May 2010</ref> Josephine Tucker Robertson, wife of Julian Robertson, died 8 June 2010 after a long fight against [[breast cancer]].<ref>[http://www.salisburypost.com/News/060910-josie-robertson- Josie Robertson dies] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612184401/http://www.salisburypost.com/News/060910-josie-robertson- |date=2010-06-12 }}, Salisburypost.com, 9 June 2010</ref>\n\nIn January 2012 Robertson donated $1.25 million to [[Restore Our Future]], a Super PAC supporting [[Mitt Romney presidential campaign, 2012|Mitt Romney's presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pro-Romney \u2018Super PAC\u2019 Spent $14 Million in January|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/02/20/pro-romney-super-pac-spent-14-million-in-january/|accessdate=20 February 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=20 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Long Island News Campaign Finance|url=http://data.newsday.com/long-island/data/augpolitics/campaign-finance/pac-presidential-donors/?fieldSelectMatchAny=no&fieldSelect-first_name=+JULIAN&fieldSelect-last_name=ROBERTSON|accessdate=16 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140519003504/http://data.newsday.com/long-island/data/augpolitics/campaign-finance/pac-presidential-donors/?fieldSelectMatchAny=no&fieldSelect-first_name=+JULIAN&fieldSelect-last_name=ROBERTSON|archivedate=19 May 2014}}</ref> In 2015, Robertson gave $1 million to a Super PAC supporting [[Jeb Bush's presidential candidacy]].<ref name=mddonors>{{cite news|title=Million-Dollar Donors in the 2016 Presidential Race|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/us/elections/top-presidential-donors-campaign-money.html|accessdate=14 October 2015|publisher=New York Times|date=25 August 2015}}</ref> In April 2016, Robertson gave $25M to [[Success Academy Charter Schools]] in New York.<ref name=\"NYPost_2016-04-12\">{{Cite news | title = Charter school network lands $25M donation from hedge fund | last = Campanile | first = Carl | newspaper = [[New York Post]] | date = 12 April 2016 | accessdate = 2016-05-01 | url = https://nypost.com/2016/04/12/charter-school-network-lands-25m-donation-from-hedge-fund/ }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT_2016-04-13\">{{Cite news | title = Success Academy Charter School Network Receives $25 Million Gift | last = Taylor | first = Kate | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 12 April 2016 | accessdate = 2016-05-01 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/13/nyregion/success-academy-charter-school-network-receives-25-million-gift.html }}</ref>\n\n== Legacy and awards ==\nIn 2008, he was inducted into Institutional Investors Alpha's Hedge Fund Manager Hall of Fame along with [[Alfred Winslow Jones|Alfred Jones]], [[Bruce Kovner]], [[David F. Swensen|David Swensen]], [[George Soros]], [[Jack Nash (businessman)|Jack Nash]], [[James Harris Simons|James Simons]], [[Kenneth C. Griffin|Kenneth Griffin]], [[Leon Levy]], [[Louis Bacon]], [[Michael Steinhardt]], [[Paul Tudor Jones]], [[Seth Klarman]] and [[Steven A. Cohen]].<ref name=\"InstitutionalInvestor2008September23\">{{cite news|title=Cohen, Simons, 12 Others Enter Hedge Fund Hall|url=https://www.institutionalinvestor.com/article/b18bl36h7n2yzt/cohen-simons-12-others-enter-hedge-fund-hall|accessdate=16 June 2019|agency=Institutional Investor LLC|publisher=Institutional Investor|date=23 September 2008|language=English|url-access=limited }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill alumni|List of University of North Carolina-Chapel Hill people]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite news |url= |title= 'The best instincts in the jungle.' (money manager Julian Robertson) |work= [[Forbes]] |first=Frederick |last= Rowe |publisher= Forbes, Inc. |page= 78  |date=September 16, 1991}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [http://www.investopedia.com/university/greatest/julianrobertson.asp The Greatest Investors - Julian Robertson]\n* Strachman, Daniel A. Julian Robertson: A Tiger in the land of Bulls and Bears. New York: Wiley, 2004\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Kauri Cliffs Lodge}}\n{{Commons category-inline|The Farm at Cape Kidnappers}}\n* [http://money.cnn.com/2008/01/28/news/newsmakers/okeefe_tiger.fortune/index.htm?postversion=2008012909 Tiger's Julian Robertson Roars Again] \u2014 ''Fortune/CNN Money'', 1/28/08\n* [http://fundville.com/blog/2010/03/the-ultimate-guide-to-tiger-cubs-and-tiger-seeds/ The Ultimate Guide to Tiger Cubs and Tiger Seeds] \u2014 ''Fundville'', 3/30/10\n* [http://www.opalesque.tv/videos/Julian_Robertson Video: Julian Robertson on Tiger Cubs and Tiger Seeds (hedge funds financed by him) and his estates in New Zealand] \u2014 ''Opalesque FIVE Minutes'', 11/19/09\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robertson, Julian}}\n\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century philanthropists]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American financial analysts]]\n[[Category:American hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:American investors]]\n[[Category:American money managers]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:American stockbrokers]]\n[[Category:American stock traders]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Episcopal High School (Alexandria, Virginia) alumni]]\n[[Category:Giving Pledgers]]\n[[Category:Honorary Knights Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Salisbury, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Stock and commodity market managers]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American businessman}}\n{{about||the English badminton player|Julian Robertson (badminton)|the British First Sea Lord|Julian Oswald}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Julian Robertson\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Julian Hart Robertson Jr.\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1932|6|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[Salisbury, North Carolina]], US\n| residence          = [[Locust Valley, New York]], U.S.\n| nationality        = American\n| alma_mater         = [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]\n| occupation         = Hedge fund manager and philanthropist\n| employer           = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|Josephine Tucker Robertson|1972|2010|reason=her death}}\n| networth           = [[US$]]4.4 billion (November 2019)<ref name=\"forbes.com\" />\n}}\n'''Julian Hart Robertson Jr.''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|KNZMh}} (born June 25, 1932)<ref>{{Cite news| url = http://www.nndb.com/people/260/000163768/|title=Julian H. Robertson Jr.|publisher=[[NNDB]] |accessdate = September 20, 2014}}</ref> is an American billionaire [[hedge fund|hedge fund manager]], and philanthropist. Now retired, Robertson invests in other hedge funds, mostly those run by former employees of his own defunct hedge fund company, [[Tiger Management]]. The so-called ''Tiger cubs'' manage around 50 of the world's top hedge funds, including Stephen Mandal's Lone Pine, Andreas Halvorsen's Viking, Rob Citrone's Discovery Capital Management, Philippe Laffont of Coatue Management, Lee Ainslie of Maverick Capital and [[Chase Coleman III|Chase Coleman]] of Tiger Global Management.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.valuewalk.com/2017/01/julian-robertson-start-management-avoid-reits/|title=Julian Robertson \u2013 Start With Management & Avoid REIT\u2019s|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He is a signatory of [[The Giving Pledge]].\n\nRobertson founded Tiger Management, one of the earliest hedge funds. Robertson is credited with turning $8 million in start-up capital in 1980 into over $22 billion in the late 1990s, though that was followed by a rapid downward spiral of investor withdrawals that ended with the fund closing in 2000.<ref>{{Cite news| url =http://money.cnn.com/2000/03/30/mutualfunds/q_funds_tiger/|title= Tiger Management closes |author= Jennifer Karchmer |publisher=[[CNNMoney]] |date =March 30, 2000}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, his compensation and share of Tiger's gain exceeded $300 million. His 2003 estimated net worth was over $400 million, and in December 2017 it was estimated by ''[[Forbes]]'' at $4.1 billion.<ref name=\"forbes.com\">[https://www.forbes.com/profile/julian-robertson Julian Robertson - Forbes], Forbes.com. Accessed May 2015.</ref> Robertson said in 2008 that he shorted subprime securities and made money through credit default swaps.<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/2008/01/28/news/newsmakers/okeefe_tiger.fortune/index.htm Tiger's Julian Robertson Roars Again], Brian O'Keefe, ''Fortune'' Senior Editor, Jan. 28, 2008</ref> The following year, according to ''Forbes'', Robertson's return on his $200 million personal trading account was 150 percent.<ref name=\"forbes.com\"/>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRobertson is the son of Julian Hart Robertson Sr., a textile company executive, and the former Blanche Spencer.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AMlmfpPt3jwC&pg=PA20 Julian Robertson: A Tiger in the Land of Bulls and Bears], Daniel A. Strachman, Published by John Wiley and Sons, 2004, {{ISBN|0-471-32363-2}}</ref> He graduated from [[Episcopal High School (Alexandria, Virginia)|Episcopal High School]] in 1951 and the [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] in 1955.  While at Chapel Hill, he was admitted to [[Zeta Psi]] fraternity.  He then served as an officer in the [[U.S. Navy]] until 1957.<ref name=\"Rowe\">Rowe.</ref>\n\nAfter leaving the Navy, Robertson moved to New York City and worked for a time as a stockbroker for [[Kidder, Peabody & Co.]] At Kidder, he eventually headed the firm's asset management division (Webster Securities) before departing to move with his family to New Zealand for a year to write a novel. On his return, in 1980 Robertson launched [[Tiger Management]] with initial investments from friends and family.<ref name=\"Rowe\"/>\n\n==Investment career==\nOn April 1, 1996, ''[[BusinessWeek]]'' carried a cover story written by reporter [[Gary Weiss]], called \"Fall of the Wizard\", that was critical of Robertson's performance and behavior as founder and manager of Tiger Management.  Robertson subsequently sued Weiss and ''BusinessWeek'' for $1 billion for [[defamation]].  The suit was [[Settlement (litigation)|settled]] with no money changing hands and ''BusinessWeek'' standing by the substance of its reporting.<ref>\n*{{cite news |url= |title= Digital, corner newsstands go head-to-head:  Question of timing in magazine publishing goes to court |work= [[The Fresno Bee]] |first= |last= [[Associated Press]] |publisher= |page= D14  |date=November 4, 1997}}\n*{{cite news|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1G1-19460270 |title=Steep libel claims raise concerns |work=Folio:  The Magazine for Magazine Management |first=Jeff |last=Garigliano |publisher=[[Cowles Media Company|Cowles Business Media Inc.]] |page=19 |date=June 1, 1997 }}\n*{{cite news |url= |title= Money Aside, Manager Settles Suit |work= [[New York Daily News]] |first= Keith J. |last= Kelly |publisher= |page= 78  |date=December 18, 1997}}\n*{{cite news |url= |title= Corrections  |work=[[New York Times]] |publisher= |date= January 7, 1997}}\n*{{cite news |url= |title= Investor files papers signaling intent to sue Business Week for $1 billion |work= [[Wall Street Journal]] |first= Patrick M. |last= Reilly |publisher= [[Dow Jones & Company|Dow Jones]]   |date=April 4, 1997}}\n*{{cite news |url= |title= Business Week Agrees to Settle Libel Suit Brought by Investor  |work=[[Wall Street Journal]] |publisher= [[Dow Jones & Company|Dow Jones]] |date=December 18, 1997}}\n*{{cite news\n |last=Pogrebin \n |first=Robin \n |date=November 3, 1997 \n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/11/03/business/publication-date-open-to-dispute-in-internet-age.html?scp=1&sq=Publication%20Date%20Open%20to%20Dispute%20In%20Internet%20Age&st=cse \n |title=Publication Date Open to Dispute In Internet Age \n |format=Newspaper article \n |work=[[New York Times]] \n |publisher= \n |accessdate=November 11, 2009 \n}}\n*{{cite news\n |last=Truell \n |first=Peter \n |date=December 18, 1997 \n |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/18/business/the-media-business-investor-settles-libel-suit-against-business-week.html?scp=1&sq=Investor%20Settles%20Libel%20Suit%20Against%20Business%20Week&st=cse \n |title=The Media Business;  Investor Settles Libel Suit Against Business Week \n |format=Newspaper article \n |work=[[New York Times]] \n |publisher= \n |accessdate=November 11, 2009 \n}}\n*{{cite web\n |last=Weiss \n |first=Gary \n |date=April 1, 1996 \n |url=http://www.businessweek.com/1996/14/b34692.htm \n |title=Fall of the Wizard \n |format=Magazine article \n |work=[[Business Week]] \n |publisher=[[McGraw-Hill]] \n |accessdate=November 11, 2009 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091216034434/http://www.businessweek.com/1996/14/b34692.htm \n |archivedate=December 16, 2009 \n}}</ref>\n\nThe Tiger funds reached a peak of $22 billion in assets in 1998. Robertson's Tiger Fund accurately predicted the [[Tech Bubble]], purposely underweighting the sector due to the overpricing of technology securities in comparison to their earnings and earning potential. So, though Tiger underperformed the S&P 500 in the short term, the fund accurately predicted the underlying flaw in the market. \"The proportion invested into technology stocks by Tiger Management, for example, a well-known value-manager, is low. In 1999 Tiger eliminated virtually all investments in this segment. This is consistent with the widely reported refusal of Julian Robertson, manager of the Tiger Fund, to buy into the internet bubble.\"<ref name=\"investopedia_2015\">{{citation |author=Loth, Richard |url=http://www.investopedia.com/university/greatest/julianrobertson.asp |title=The Greatest Investors: Julian Robertson |work=[[Investopedia]] |accessdate=2015-11-19 }}</ref>\n\nTiger's largest equity holding at that time was [[U.S. Airways]], whose troubles dragged down the value of his holdings. Such missteps ultimately led him to close his investment company in March 2000 and return all outside capital to investors. Tiger earlier made $2 billion in gains but then gave most of them back during a huge one-day move in the yen in 1998. In September 2001, Robertson distributed 24.8 million greatly devalued U.S. Airways shares to former Tiger investors. Robertson declared his intent to hold onto his own stock in the airline.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2001/09/23/business/investing-diary-left-holding-the-bag-on-us-airways-stock.html \"Investing Diary; Left Holding the Bag On US Airways Stock\"], by Laurence Zuckerman, September 23, 2001</ref>\n\n==After Tiger==\n[[File:Flickr - RalphJB - Kauri Cliffs Lodge (6).jpg|thumb|Kauri Cliffs Lodge near [[Matauri Bay]]]]\nAfter closing his fund in 2000, Robertson kept his hand in the hedge fund business by supporting and financing upcoming hedge fund managers (38 in total as of September 2009), in return for a stake in their fund  management companies. Apart from those, many of the analysts and managers Robertson employed and mentored at Tiger Management, including Chris Shumway, [[Lee Ainslie]] and [[Ole Andreas Halvorsen]] went out on their own and are now running some of the best-known hedge fund firms, called \"Tiger Cubs\".<ref>[http://www.opalesque.com/tiger - list of 38 Tiger Seeds and 32 Tiger Cubs]</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2012/07/30/business/The-Tiger-and-His-Cubs.html \"The Tiger and His Cubs,\"] New York Times, July 30, 2012</ref> These include funds such as [[Viking Global Investors]], Tiger Legatus, Tiger Veda, [[Blue Ridge Capital]], [[JAT Capital Management]], Tiger Global, [[Maverick Capital]], [[Coatue Management]], Nehal Chopra's Tiger Ratan Capital Fund NA<ref>Copeland, Rob, [https://www.wsj.com/articles/hedge-fund-prodigy-takes-a-300-million-hit-1447027806 \"Hedge-Fund Prodigy Takes a $300 Million Hit\"], Wall Street ''Journal'', November 8, 2015. Earlier in 2015, Chopra became 'one of the few women to manage more than $1 billion in an industry long dominated by men'. Retrieved 2015-11-09.</ref><ref>Vardi, Nathan, [https://www.forbes.com/sites/nathanvardi/2015/07/24/nehal-chopra-runs-circles-around-the-boys-with-top-performing-hedge-fund/ \"Nehal Chopra Runs Circles Around The Boys With Top Performing Hedge Fund\"], ''Forbes'', July 24, 2015. Retrieved 2015-11-09.</ref> among others.\n\nRobertson is the founder and benefactor of the [[Robertson Scholars Program]] which awards a merit scholarship that provides four-year full-tuition, room, and board, and travel funding for 36 [[Duke University]] and [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]] students each year.\n\nIn August 2010, Robertson signed [[The Giving Pledge]], an initiative by software mogul [[Bill Gates]] and investor [[Warren Buffett]] in which the wealthy would pledge at least half their assets to charity.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2010/aug/04/us-billionaires-half-fortune-gates |title=US billionaires club together \u2013 to give away half their fortunes to good causes |work=The Guardian |date=4 August 2010 | location=London | first=Andrew | last=Clark}}</ref>\n\nHe also is active as an investor and developer in [[New Zealand]], where he spends some time. His family owns three lodges: Kauri Cliffs Lodge near [[Matauri Bay]] in [[Northland Region|Northland]]; Matakauri Lodge [[Queenstown, New Zealand|Queenstown]]; and The Farm at [[Cape Kidnappers]], [[Hawke's Bay region|Hawkes Bay]], as well as several wineries. Robertson was appointed an [[New Zealand Order of Merit|Honorary Knight Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]], for services to business and philanthropy, in the [[2010 New Year Honours (New Zealand)|2010 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10617907 |title=New Year Honours: Full 2010 list |work=The New Zealand Herald |date=31 December 2009 }}</ref> In 2009, it was announced that Robertson would donate art valued at $115 million to the [[Auckland Art Gallery Toi o T\u0101maki|Auckland Art Gallery]]. The donation included works by [[Paul Cezanne]], [[Paul Gauguin]], [[Pablo Picasso]], [[Henri Matisse]], [[Piet Mondrian]], [[Salvador Dali]], [[Georges Braque]], [[Andre Derain]], [[Fernand Leger]], [[Pierre Bonnard]] and [[Henri Fantin-Latour]] and was the largest of its kind in Australasia.<ref name=nzdonation>{{cite news |last=Herrick|first=Linda |date=9 February 2009 |title=Picassos among $115m gift to Auckland |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10571094 |work=NZ Herald |location= |access-date=15 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2010 the [[New York Stem Cell Foundation]], a private research institution, received a $27 million gift from Robertson to fund its research.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704635204575242444135532502?KEYWORDS=josie+robertson Hedge-Fund Founder Bolsters Stem-Cell Research with $27 million Gift],'' The Wall Street Journal'', 14 May 2010</ref> Josephine Tucker Robertson, wife of Julian Robertson, died 8 June 2010 after a long fight against [[breast cancer]].<ref>[http://www.salisburypost.com/News/060910-josie-robertson- Josie Robertson dies] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612184401/http://www.salisburypost.com/News/060910-josie-robertson- |date=2010-06-12 }}, Salisburypost.com, 9 June 2010</ref>\n\nIn January 2012 Robertson donated $1.25 million to [[Restore Our Future]], a Super PAC supporting [[Mitt Romney presidential campaign, 2012|Mitt Romney's presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Pro-Romney \u2018Super PAC\u2019 Spent $14 Million in January|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/02/20/pro-romney-super-pac-spent-14-million-in-january/|accessdate=20 February 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=20 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Long Island News Campaign Finance|url=http://data.newsday.com/long-island/data/augpolitics/campaign-finance/pac-presidential-donors/?fieldSelectMatchAny=no&fieldSelect-first_name=+JULIAN&fieldSelect-last_name=ROBERTSON|accessdate=16 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140519003504/http://data.newsday.com/long-island/data/augpolitics/campaign-finance/pac-presidential-donors/?fieldSelectMatchAny=no&fieldSelect-first_name=+JULIAN&fieldSelect-last_name=ROBERTSON|archivedate=19 May 2014}}</ref> In 2015, Robertson gave $1 million to a Super PAC supporting [[Jeb Bush's presidential candidacy]].<ref name=mddonors>{{cite news|title=Million-Dollar Donors in the 2016 Presidential Race|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/us/elections/top-presidential-donors-campaign-money.html|accessdate=14 October 2015|publisher=New York Times|date=25 August 2015}}</ref> In April 2016, Robertson gave $25M to [[Success Academy Charter Schools]] in New York.<ref name=\"NYPost_2016-04-12\">{{Cite news | title = Charter school network lands $25M donation from hedge fund | last = Campanile | first = Carl | newspaper = [[New York Post]] | date = 12 April 2016 | accessdate = 2016-05-01 | url = https://nypost.com/2016/04/12/charter-school-network-lands-25m-donation-from-hedge-fund/ }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT_2016-04-13\">{{Cite news | title = Success Academy Charter School Network Receives $25 Million Gift | last = Taylor | first = Kate | newspaper = [[New York Times]] | date = 12 April 2016 | accessdate = 2016-05-01 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/13/nyregion/success-academy-charter-school-network-receives-25-million-gift.html }}</ref>\n\n== Legacy and awards ==\nIn 2008, he was inducted into Institutional Investors Alpha's Hedge Fund Manager Hall of Fame along with [[Alfred Winslow Jones|Alfred Jones]], [[Bruce Kovner]], [[David F. Swensen|David Swensen]], [[George Soros]], [[Jack Nash (businessman)|Jack Nash]], [[James Harris Simons|James Simons]], [[Kenneth C. Griffin|Kenneth Griffin]], [[Leon Levy]], [[Louis Bacon]], [[Michael Steinhardt]], [[Paul Tudor Jones]], [[Seth Klarman]] and [[Steven A. Cohen]].<ref name=\"InstitutionalInvestor2008September23\">{{cite news|title=Cohen, Simons, 12 Others Enter Hedge Fund Hall|url=https://www.institutionalinvestor.com/article/b18bl36h7n2yzt/cohen-simons-12-others-enter-hedge-fund-hall|accessdate=16 June 2019|agency=Institutional Investor LLC|publisher=Institutional Investor|date=23 September 2008|language=English|url-access=limited }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill alumni|List of University of North Carolina-Chapel Hill people]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n*{{cite news |url= |title= 'The best instincts in the jungle.' (money manager Julian Robertson) |work= [[Forbes]] |first=Frederick |last= Rowe |publisher= Forbes, Inc. |page= 78  |date=September 16, 1991}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* [http://www.investopedia.com/university/greatest/julianrobertson.asp The Greatest Investors - Julian Robertson]\n* Strachman, Daniel A. Julian Robertson: A Tiger in the land of Bulls and Bears. New York: Wiley, 2004\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Kauri Cliffs Lodge}}\n{{Commons category-inline|The Farm at Cape Kidnappers}}\n* [http://money.cnn.com/2008/01/28/news/newsmakers/okeefe_tiger.fortune/index.htm?postversion=2008012909 Tiger's Julian Robertson Roars Again] \u2014 ''Fortune/CNN Money'', 1/28/08\n* [http://fundville.com/blog/2010/03/the-ultimate-guide-to-tiger-cubs-and-tiger-seeds/ The Ultimate Guide to Tiger Cubs and Tiger Seeds] \u2014 ''Fundville'', 3/30/10\n* [http://www.opalesque.tv/videos/Julian_Robertson Video: Julian Robertson on Tiger Cubs and Tiger Seeds (hedge funds financed by him) and his estates in New Zealand] \u2014 ''Opalesque FIVE Minutes'', 11/19/09\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Robertson, Julian}}\n\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century philanthropists]]\n[[Category:American billionaires]]\n[[Category:American financial analysts]]\n[[Category:American hedge fund managers]]\n[[Category:American investors]]\n[[Category:American money managers]]\n[[Category:American philanthropists]]\n[[Category:American stockbrokers]]\n[[Category:American stock traders]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Episcopal High School (Alexandria, Virginia) alumni]]\n[[Category:Giving Pledgers]]\n[[Category:Honorary Knights Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Salisbury, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Stock and commodity market managers]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Bamboo10Bamboo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAfter Tiger:removing broken link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julian_Robertson"}
{"title_page": "Jimmie Nicol", "text_new": "{{short description|English drummer}}\n{{other people||James Nicol (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Jimmie Nicol\n| image            = Televisie-optreden van The Beatles in Treslong te Hillegom vlnr George Harriso, Bestanddeelnr 916-5098 (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Nicol in 1964\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = James George Nicol\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1939|8|3}}\n| birth_place      = [[London]], England, United Kingdom\n| instrument       = {{flat list|  \n* [[Drums]]\n* [[percussion]]\n}}\n| genre            = {{flat list| \n* [[Rock music|Rock]]\n* [[pop music|pop]]\n}}\n| occupation       = Drummer, business entrepreneur\n| years_active     = 1957\u20131967\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[The Beatles]], [[Georgie Fame and the Blue Flames]], [[Colin Hicks & The Cabin Boys]], [[Vince Eager]], [[Oscar Rabin]], [[Cyril Stapleton]], [[The Spotnicks]], Charlie Katz, Ray McVay, The Shubdubs\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''James George Nicol''' (born 3 August 1939) is an English drummer and business entrepreneur. He is  best known for temporarily replacing [[Ringo Starr]] in [[the Beatles]] for a series of concerts during the height of [[Beatlemania]] in 1964, elevating him from relative obscurity to worldwide fame and then back again in the space of a fortnight.<ref>He used the spelling \"Jimmie Nicol\" on his own bass drum. See the {{cite web|url=http://www.pmouse.nl/nicol |title=Jimmie Nicol page from pmouse.nl |accessdate=2006-12-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111091533/http://www.pmouse.nl/nicol |archivedate=11 January 2012 }}</ref> Nicol had hoped that his association with the Beatles would greatly enhance his career but instead found that the spotlight moved away from him once Starr returned to the group, and in 1965 his subsequent lack of commercial success culminated in bankruptcy. In 1967, after having worked with a number of different bands which included a successful relationship with [[the Spotnicks]], he left the music business to pursue a variety of entrepreneurial ventures. Over the decades, Nicol increasingly shied away from media attention, preferring not to discuss his connection to the Beatles nor seeking financial gain from it. He has a son, Howard, who is a [[BAFTA]] award-winning sound engineer.\n\n==Early career==\nJimmie Nicol's career break came in 1957 when he was talent spotted by [[Larry Parnes]] whilst drumming with various bands in London's [[The 2i's Coffee Bar]], a time that saw Britain's [[skiffle]]-dominated music scene giving way to [[rock and roll]] which  was being popularised by its [[Teddy Boy]] youth. Parnes invited Nicol to join [[Colin Hicks & The Cabin Boys]] whom Parnes co-managed with John Kennedy (Colin Hicks is the younger brother of English entertainer [[Tommy Steele]], whom Parnes also managed). After taking a temporary break from the group to be a member of the original [[pit band]] in the [[Lionel Bart]] musical ''[[Fings Ain't Wot They Used T'Be]]'' at the [[Theatre Royal Stratford East]] Nicol rejoined Hicks's band for their appearance in the 1958 Italian film documentary ''Europa Di Notte'', breaking them in Italy and subsequently allowing them to tour there extensively.{{sfn|Norman|2009|pp=180}} During the early sixties, Nicol went on to play for a number of artists, including [[Vince Eager]], [[Oscar Rabin]], and [[Cyril Stapleton]] and was kept in regular work through Charlie Katz, a well-known session fixer during that period. Nicol has cited drummer [[Phil Seamen]] and saxophonist [[Julian \"Cannonball\" Adderley]] as being his main influences.{{sfn|pmouse.nl|2010}}\n\nIn 1964 Nicol helped to form The Shubdubs with former [[The Merseybeats|Merseybeats]] bassist Bob Garner, a jazz line-up similar in musical style to [[Georgie Fame and the Blue Flames]], a group with whom Nicol had sat-in with when they were the resident house band at London's now defunct [[Flamingo Jazz Club]]. Other members of The Shubdubs were [[Tony Allen (vocalist)|Tony Allen]] (vocals), [[Johnny Harris (musician)|Johnny Harris]] (trumpet), Quincy Davis (tenor saxophone), and [[Roger Coulam]] (organ \u2013 went on to form [[Blue Mink]]). It was at this point that he received a telephone call from [[the Beatles]]' producer, [[George Martin]]. Nicol recalled: \"I was having a bit of a lie down after lunch when the phone rang.\"{{sfn|Harry|1992|pp=484}}\n\n==With the Beatles==\nWhen [[Ringo Starr]] collapsed with [[tonsillitis]] and was hospitalised on 3 June 1964, the eve of the Beatles' 1964 [[Australasia]]n tour, the band's manager [[Brian Epstein]] and their producer [[George Martin]] urgently discussed the feasibility of using a stand-in drummer rather than cancelling part of the tour. Martin suggested Jimmie Nicol as he had recently used him on a recording session with [[Tommy Quickly]].{{sfn|Harry|1992|pp=484}} Nicol had also drummed on a 'Top Six' budget label album as part of an uncredited session band, as well as an [[extended play]] single (with three tracks on each side) of Beatles [[cover versions]] (marketed as 'Teenagers Choice' and titled ''Beatlemania'') which meant that he already knew the songs and their arrangements. Producer Bill Wellings and Shubdubs trumpeter Johnny Harris (freelancing as an arranger and composer) were responsible for putting together alternative budget cover versions of songs taken from the British [[Hit Parade]] aimed at cash-strapped teenagers. Harris said: \"The idea was for me to try and guess which six songs would be topping the charts about a month ahead. I would do the arrangements and then go into the studio and record 'sound a-likes'; the first EP (extended play) released got to number 30 in the charts. Jimmie was on drums and, as you can imagine, we covered a lot of the Beatles' songs.\"{{sfn|Darren Stuart 2012}} Although [[John Lennon]] and [[Paul McCartney]] quickly accepted the idea of using an understudy, [[George Harrison]] threatened to pull out of the tour telling Epstein and Martin: \"If Ringo's not going, then neither am I. You can find two replacements.\"{{sfn|Badman|2000|pp=101}} Martin recalled: \"They nearly didn't do the Australia tour. George is a very loyal person. It took all of Brian's and my persuasion to tell George that if he didn't do it he was letting everybody down.\"{{sfn|The Beatles|2000|pp=139}} [[Tony Barrow]], who was the Beatles' press officer at the time, later commented: \"Brian saw it as the lesser of two evils; cancel the tour and upset thousands of fans or continue and upset the Beatles.\"{{sfn|Mojo|2002|pp=108}} Ringo stated that \"it was very strange, them going off without me. They'd taken Jimmie Nicol and I thought they didn't love me any more \u2013 all that stuff went through my head.\"{{sfn|The Beatles|2000|pp=139}} The arrangements were made very quickly, from a telephone call to Nicol at his home in West London inviting him to attend an audition/rehearsal at [[Abbey Road Studios]],{{sfn|Harry|1992|pp=45}} to packing his bags, all in the same day.{{sfn|Norman|1993|pp=231}} At a press conference a reporter mischievously asked John Lennon why [[Pete Best]], who had been the Beatles' previous drummer for two years but dismissed by the group on the eve of stardom, was not being given the opportunity of replacing Ringo, to which Lennon replied: \"He's got his own group [Pete Best & the All Stars], and it might have looked as if we were taking him back, which is not good for him.\"{{sfn|Badman|2000|pp=103}}\n\n[[File:The Beatles (with Jimmy Nicol) 1964 001.png|thumb|left|McCartney, Harrison, Lennon, and Nicol in the [[Netherlands]] on 5 June 1964]]\nNicol's first concert with the Beatles took place just 27 hours later on 4 June at the KB Hallen in [[Copenhagen, Denmark]]. He was given the distinctive Beatle [[moptop]] hairstyle, put on Ringo's suit and went on stage to an audience of 4,500 Beatles fans. McCartney recalled: \"He was sitting up on this rostrum just eyeing up all the women. We'd start '[[She Loves You]]': [counting in] 'one, two', nothing, 'one, two', and still nothing!\" Their set was reduced from eleven songs to ten, dropping Ringo's vocal spot of \"[[I Wanna Be Your Man]]\".{{sfn|Mojo|2002|pp=108}} McCartney teasingly sent Starr a telegram saying: \"Hurry up and get well Ringo, Jimmy is wearing out all your suits.\"{{sfn|Harry|1992|pp=484}} Commenting later on the fickle nature of his brief celebrity, Nicol reflected: \"The day before I was a Beatle, girls weren't interested in me at all. The day after, with the suit and the Beatle cut, riding in the back of the limo with John and Paul, they were dying to get a touch of me. It was very strange and quite scary.\" He was also able to shed some light on how they passed the time between shows: \"I thought I could drink and lay women with the best of them until I caught up with these guys.\"{{sfn|Q|2010|pp=56}}\n\nIn the [[Netherlands]], Nicol and Lennon allegedly spent a whole night at a brothel.{{sfn|Mojo|2002|pp=108}} Lennon said: \"It was some kind of scene on the road. [[Satyricon]]! There's photographs of me grovelling about, crawling about Amsterdam on my knees, coming out of whorehouses, and people saying 'Good morning John'. The police escorted me to these places because they never wanted a big scandal. When we hit town, we hit it \u2013 we were not pissing about. We had [the women]. They were great. We didn't call them groupies, then; I've forgotten what we called them, something like 'slags'.\"{{sfn|Q|2010|pp=56}}{{sfn|The Beatles|2000|pp=139}} By then the Beatles were becoming more restricted by their increasing fame and spending most of their free time inside hotel suites. But Nicol discovered that, aside from acting as a Beatle, he could behave much as any tourist could: \"I often went out alone. Hardly anybody recognised me and I was able to wander around. In Hong Kong, I went to see the thousands of people who live on little boats in the harbour. I saw the refugees in [[Kowloon]], and I visited a nightclub. I like to see life. A Beatle could never really do that.\"{{sfn|Badman|2000|pp=110}}\n\nNicol played a total of eight shows until Starr rejoined the group in Melbourne, Australia, on 14 June. He was unable to say goodbye to the Beatles as they were still asleep when he left, and he did not want to disturb them. At Melbourne Airport, Epstein presented him with a cheque for \u00a3500 and a gold [[Eterna|Eterna-matic]] wrist watch inscribed: \"From the Beatles and Brian Epstein to Jimmy \u2013 with appreciation and gratitude.\"{{sfn|Harry|1992|pp=484}} George Martin later paid tribute to Nicol whilst recognising the problems he experienced in trying to readjust to a normal life again: \"Jimmie Nicol was a very good drummer who came along and learnt Ringo's parts very well. He did the job excellently, and faded into obscurity immediately afterwards.\"{{sfn|The Beatles|2000|pp=139}} Paul McCartney acknowledged: \"It wasn't an easy thing for Jimmy to stand in for Ringo, and have all that fame thrust upon him. And the minute his tenure was over, he wasn't famous any more.\" Nicol himself expressed his disillusionment several years later: \"Standing in for Ringo was the worst thing that ever happened to me. Until then I was quite happy earning \u00a330 or \u00a340 a week. After the headlines died, I began dying too.\"{{sfn|Mojo|2002|pp=108}} He resisted the temptation to sell his story, stating in a rare 1987 interview: \"After the money ran low, I thought of cashing-in in some way or other. But the timing wasn't right. And I didn't want to step on the Beatles' toes. They had been damn good for me and to me.\"\n\n==Later career and life==\nNicol reformed the Shubdubs, renaming themselves Jimmy Nicol and the Shubdubs. They released two singles \"Husky\"/\"Don't Come Back\", followed by \"Humpty Dumpty\"/\"Night Train\"; neither of which was a commercial success. He was later called upon to again stand in for an ailing drummer when Dave Clark of [[The Dave Clark Five]] fell ill and Nicol's band, Jimmy Nicol and the Shubdubs, filled in for The Dave Clark Five in [[Blackpool, Lancashire]].{{sfn|Harry|1992|pp=484}} Whilst there Nicol was reminded of just how popular, albeit briefly, he had been as a stand-in Beatle; receiving a bundle of 5,000 fan letters passed on to him from an Australian radio disc jockey. Nicol sent a message back thanking the fans, promising that he would one day return to Australia permanently.{{sfn|Harry|1992|pp=484}} He was later reunited with the Beatles when his band appeared on the same bill as them and [[The Fourmost]] on 12 July 1964 at the [[Brighton Hippodrome|Hippodrome]] in [[Brighton]]. In 1965 Nicol declared bankruptcy with debts of \u00a34,066, nine months after being a temporary Beatle.{{sfn|Mojo|2002|pp=108}} Later that year he joined the successful Swedish group [[the Spotnicks]], recording with them and twice touring the world. He left them in 1967, spending time in Mexico studying [[samba]] and [[bossa nova]] rhythms, whilst also diversifying into business. In 1975 he returned to England and became involved with housing renovations. In 1988 it was rumoured that Nicol had died,{{sfn|pmouse.nl|2010}}, the year after making his final interview and four years after his 1984 appearance at a Beatles convention in [[Amsterdam]], but an article in 2005 by the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' claimed that he was still alive and living in London, refusing to do any interviews or talk about his tenure with the Beatles. It was later asserted by the same source that he had moved to [[Mexico]] in 2013 with his then-wife and was still living there as of 2017, despite family and friends having no contact with him.<ref>Daily Mail, 2017</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nDuring Nicol's brief time with the Beatles both Lennon and McCartney would often ask him how he felt he was coping, to which his reply would usually be \"It's getting better\". Three years later McCartney was walking his dog, Martha, with [[Hunter Davies]], the Beatles official biographer, when the sun came out. McCartney remarked that the weather was \"getting better\" and began to laugh, remembering Nicol. This event inspired the song \"[[Getting Better]]\" on 1967's ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]''.{{sfn|Miles|1998|pp=313}} McCartney again makes reference to Nicol on the ''[[Let It Be (Beatles album)|Let It Be]]'' tapes from 1969, saying: \"I think you'll find we're not going abroad 'cause Ringo just said he doesn't want to go abroad. You know, he put his foot down. Although Jimmie Nicol might go abroad.\"  \n\nWhile appearing on the radio show ''Fresh Air'' hosted by [[Terry Gross]] in April 2016, [[Tom Hanks]] noted that he was at least partly influenced by Jimmie Nicol's experience with the Beatles when he wrote the script for his 1996 feature film ''[[That Thing You Do!]]''<ref name=\"fa\">{{Cite AV media| time=12:46 |work=[[Fresh Air]] |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=April 26, 2016 |title=Tom Hanks Says Self-Doubt Is 'A High-Wire Act That We All Walk'}}</ref>\n\n==Discography and performance history==\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!1950s\n|colspan=2| \n*Choir boy at Honeywell Road School, [[Wandsworth]], in London.\n*The [[Boys' Brigade]] (percussion).\n*[[Army Cadet Force|Army Cadet]] [[Military Band]] (percussion and xylophone).\n*For a short time, Nicol also worked as a drum repairer for (UK) musical instrument distributor ''Boosey & Hawkes''.\n|-\n!1957\u20131958\n|colspan=2| Colin Hicks & The Cabin Boys. (Colin Hicks is the younger brother of British rock 'n' roll star [[Tommy Steele]]).\n:Singles released:\n:*Pye 7N15114 \"Wild Eyes And Tender Lips\" / \"Empty Arms Blues\"\n:*Pye 7N15125 \"La Dee Dah\" / \"Wasteland\"\n:*Pye 7N15163 \"Little Boy Blue\" / \"Jamabalaya\"\n|-\n!1959\u20131960\n|colspan=2| [[Vince Eager]] and the Quiet Three.\n|-\n!1960\n|colspan=2| [[Oscar Rabin Band]].\n|-\n!1961\n|colspan=2| [[Cyril Stapleton]] Big Band.\n|-\n!1961\u20131963\n|colspan=2| Session work (including jobs with musicians from the orchestras of [[Ted Heath (bandleader)|Ted Heath]] and [[Johnny Dankworth]]).\n|-\n!1964 || \n| The Shubdubs.\n:Singles released:\n:* \"Humpty Dumpty\" / \"Night Train\" \u2013 [[Pye Records|Pye]] 7N15623 2/1964 / US: Mar\u2013Mar Records 313 1964\n:* \"Husky\" / \"Please Come Back\" \u2013 Pye 7N15666 6/1964 (credited to 'Jimmy Nicol')\n:* \"Baby Please Don't Go\" / \"Shubdubery\" \u2013 Pye 7N15699 10/1964\n|-\n!1964 || April / May\n| Touring with [[Georgie Fame]] and The Blue Flames.\n|-\n!1964 || June\n| The Beatles (as temporary stand in for Ringo Starr).\n*4 June 1964: KB Hallen, Copenhagen, Denmark.\n*5 June 1964: Treslong, Hillegom, the Netherlands, (recording TV show, VARA).\n*6 June 1964: Auction Hall (Veilinghal), Blokker, the Netherlands.\n*9 June 1964: Princess Theatre, [[Kowloon]], Hong Kong.\n*12 June 1964: [[Centennial Hall, Adelaide]], Australia.\n*13 June 1964: Centennial Hall, Adelaide, Australia.\n|-\n!1964\u20131965\n|colspan=2| Touring as: Jimmy Nicol & The Shubdubs\n:Solo single release as: The Sound of Jimmy Nicol\n:*\"Sweet Clementine\" / \"Roaring Blue\" \u2013 Decca F12017\n|-\n!1965\u20131967\n|colspan=2| [[The Spotnicks]].\n:Single release by: The Spotnicks Introducing Jimmie Nicol \n:*\"Husky\" / \"Drum Diddley\" \u2013 SweDisc SWES 1111\n|-\n!1967\n|colspan=2| Nicol lived in Mexico working with [[samba]] & [[bossa nova]] groups. He married and had a son, Howard, who in the 1990s won an award for his work as sound engineer on a BBC collection of Beatles recordings.\n|-\n!1969\n|colspan=2|Jimmie Nicol Show:\n:*\"Jumpin' Jack Flash\" / \"Era Psicodelica Del A Go Go\" \u2013 Discos Orfeon LP-E-12-623 (Mexico)(LP) (Sung in Spanish).\n|-\n!1971\n|colspan=2|\"Blue Rain\" (Mexican rock group recording in Nicol's house).\n|}\nInformation compiled from {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111091533/http://www.pmouse.nl/nicol |date=11 January 2012 }}\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Scot Halpin]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=22em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book\n|last=Norman\n|first=Philip\n|authorlink=Philip Norman (author)\n|year=2009\n|title=John Lennon\n|publisher=Harper\n|location=London\n|isbn=978-0-00-719742-2\n|ref=harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Badman\n|first=Keith\n|year=2000\n|title=The Beatles Off The Record\n|ref=harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|author=The Beatles\n|year=2000\n|authorlink=The Beatles\n|title=The Beatles Anthology\n|publisher=Cassell & Co\n|location=London\n|isbn=0-304-35605-0\n|ref=harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Harry\n|first=Bill\n|year=1992\n|authorlink=Bill Harry\n|title=The Ultimate Beatles Encyclopedia\n|publisher=Virgin Books\n|location=London\n|isbn=0-86369-681-3\n|ref=harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Stuart\n|first=Darren\n|year=2002\n|title=Johnny Harris \u2013 Movements CD & 2LP\n|publisher=Warner Bros\n|location=London\n|ref=harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Miles\n|first=Barry\n|year=1998\n|authorlink=Barry Miles\n|title=Paul McCartney: Many Years From Now\n|publisher=Vintage\n|location=London\n|isbn=0-7493-8658-4\n|ref=harv\n}}\n*{{cite journal\n|work=Mojo\n|title=Special Limited Edition # M-04951\n|year=2002\n|ref={{SfnRef|Mojo|2002}}\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Norman\n|first=Philip\n|year=1993\n|title=Shout!\n|publisher=Penguin Books\n|location=London\n|isbn=0-14-017410-9\n|ref=harv\n}}\n*{{cite journal\n|work=Q\n|year=2010\n|title=Collectors Limited Edition\n|ref={{SfnRef|Q|2010}}\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Baker\n|first=Glenn A.\n|year=1983\n|authorlink=Glenn A. Baker\n|title=The Beatles down under : the 1964 Australia & New Zealand tour\n|publisher=Wild & Woolley\n|location=Sydney\n|isbn=\n|ref=\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Berkenstadt\n|first=Jim \n|year=2013\n|title=The Beatle Who Vanished\n|publisher=Rock and Roll Detective LLC\n|isbn=0985667702\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Brown\n|first=Craig \n|year=2020\n|title=One Two Three Four: The Beatles in Time\n|publisher=4th Estate\n|isbn=978-0-00-834000-1\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|title=Jimmie Nicol |work=pmouse.nl |year=2010 |url=http://www.pmouse.nl/nicol |ref={{SfnRef|pmouse.nl|2010}} |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111091533/http://www.pmouse.nl/nicol |archivedate=11 January 2012 }}\n*{{discogs artist}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140201221045/http://www.feenotes.com/db/artists/n/nicoljimmy.php Biography] at feenotes.com\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nicol, Jimmie}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:English rock drummers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from London]]\n[[Category:The Beatles]]\n[[Category:English session musicians]]\n[[Category:British expatriates in Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English drummer}}\n{{other people||James Nicol (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Jimmie Nicol\n| image            = Televisie-optreden van The Beatles in Treslong te Hillegom vlnr George Harriso, Bestanddeelnr 916-5098 (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Nicol in 1964\n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = James George Nicol\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1939|8|3}}\n| birth_place      = [[London]], England, United Kingdom\n| instrument       = {{flat list|  \n* [[Drums]]\n* [[percussion]]\n}}\n| genre            = {{flat list| \n* [[Rock music|Rock]]\n* [[pop music|pop]]\n}}\n| occupation       = Drummer, business entrepreneur\n| years_active     = 1957\u20131967\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[The Beatles]], [[Georgie Fame and the Blue Flames]], [[Colin Hicks & The Cabin Boys]], [[Vince Eager]], [[Oscar Rabin]], [[Cyril Stapleton]], [[The Spotnicks]], Charlie Katz, Ray McVay, The Shubdubs\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''James George Nicol''' (born 3 August 1939) is an English drummer and business entrepreneur. He is  best known for temporarily replacing [[Ringo Starr]] in [[the Beatles]] for a series of concerts during the height of [[Beatlemania]] in 1964, elevating him from relative obscurity to worldwide fame and then back again in the space of a fortnight.<ref>He used the spelling \"Jimmie Nicol\" on his own bass drum. See the {{cite web|url=http://www.pmouse.nl/nicol |title=Jimmie Nicol page from pmouse.nl |accessdate=2006-12-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111091533/http://www.pmouse.nl/nicol |archivedate=11 January 2012 }}</ref> Nicol had hoped that his association with the Beatles would greatly enhance his career but instead found that the spotlight moved away from him once Starr returned to the group, and in 1965 his subsequent lack of commercial success culminated in bankruptcy. In 1967, after having worked with a number of different bands which included a successful relationship with [[the Spotnicks]], he left the music business to pursue a variety of entrepreneurial ventures. Over the decades, Nicol increasingly shied away from media attention, preferring not to discuss his connection to the Beatles nor seeking financial gain from it. He has a son, Howard, who is a [[BAFTA]] award-winning sound engineer.\n\n==Early career==\nJimmie Nicol's career break came in 1957 when he was talent spotted by [[Larry Parnes]] whilst drumming with various bands in London's [[The 2i's Coffee Bar]], a time that saw Britain's [[skiffle]]-dominated music scene giving way to [[rock and roll]] which  was being popularised by its [[Teddy Boy]] youth. Parnes invited Nicol to join [[Colin Hicks & The Cabin Boys]] whom Parnes co-managed with John Kennedy (Colin Hicks is the younger brother of English entertainer [[Tommy Steele]], whom Parnes also managed). After taking a temporary break from the group to be a member of the original [[pit band]] in the [[Lionel Bart]] musical ''[[Fings Ain't Wot They Used T'Be]]'' at the [[Theatre Royal Stratford East]] Nicol rejoined Hicks's band for their appearance in the 1958 Italian film documentary ''Europa Di Notte'', breaking them in Italy and subsequently allowing them to tour there extensively.{{sfn|Norman|2009|pp=180}} During the early sixties, Nicol went on to play for a number of artists, including [[Vince Eager]], [[Oscar Rabin]], and [[Cyril Stapleton]] and was kept in regular work through Charlie Katz, a well-known session fixer during that period. Nicol has cited drummer [[Phil Seamen]] and saxophonist [[Julian \"Cannonball\" Adderley]] as being his main influences.{{sfn|pmouse.nl|2010}}\n\nIn 1964 Nicol helped to form The Shubdubs with former [[The Merseybeats|Merseybeats]] bassist Bob Garner, a jazz line-up similar in musical style to [[Georgie Fame and the Blue Flames]], a group with whom Nicol had sat-in with when they were the resident house band at London's now defunct [[Flamingo Jazz Club]]. Other members of The Shubdubs were [[Tony Allen (vocalist)|Tony Allen]] (vocals), [[Johnny Harris (musician)|Johnny Harris]] (trumpet), Quincy Davis (tenor saxophone), and [[Roger Coulam]] (organ \u2013 went on to form [[Blue Mink]]). It was at this point that he received a telephone call from [[the Beatles]]' producer, [[George Martin]]. Nicol recalled: \"I was having a bit of a lie down after lunch when the phone rang.\"{{sfn|Harry|1992|pp=484}}\n\n==With the Beatles==\nWhen [[Ringo Starr]] collapsed with [[tonsillitis]] and was hospitalised on 3 June 1964, the eve of the Beatles' 1964 [[Australasia]]n tour, the band's manager [[Brian Epstein]] and their producer [[George Martin]] urgently discussed the feasibility of using a stand-in drummer rather than cancelling part of the tour. Martin suggested Jimmie Nicol as he had recently used him on a recording session with [[Tommy Quickly]].{{sfn|Harry|1992|pp=484}} Nicol had also drummed on a 'Top Six' budget label album as part of an uncredited session band, as well as an [[extended play]] single (with three tracks on each side) of Beatles [[cover versions]] (marketed as 'Teenagers Choice' and titled ''Beatlemania'') which meant that he already knew the songs and their arrangements. Producer Bill Wellings and Shubdubs trumpeter Johnny Harris (freelancing as an arranger and composer) were responsible for putting together alternative budget cover versions of songs taken from the British [[Hit Parade]] aimed at cash-strapped teenagers. Harris said: \"The idea was for me to try and guess which six songs would be topping the charts about a month ahead. I would do the arrangements and then go into the studio and record 'sound a-likes'; the first EP (extended play) released got to number 30 in the charts. Jimmie was on drums and, as you can imagine, we covered a lot of the Beatles' songs.\"{{sfn|Darren Stuart 2012}} Although [[John Lennon]] and [[Paul McCartney]] quickly accepted the idea of using an understudy, [[George Harrison]] threatened to pull out of the tour telling Epstein and Martin: \"If Ringo's not going, then neither am I. You can find two replacements.\"{{sfn|Badman|2000|pp=101}} Martin recalled: \"They nearly didn't do the Australia tour. George is a very loyal person. It took all of Brian's and my persuasion to tell George that if he didn't do it he was letting everybody down.\"{{sfn|The Beatles|2000|pp=139}} [[Tony Barrow]], who was the Beatles' press officer at the time, later commented: \"Brian saw it as the lesser of two evils; cancel the tour and upset thousands of fans or continue and upset the Beatles.\"{{sfn|Mojo|2002|pp=108}} Ringo stated that \"it was very strange, them going off without me. They'd taken Jimmie Nicol and I thought they didn't love me any more \u2013 all that stuff went through my head.\"{{sfn|The Beatles|2000|pp=139}} The arrangements were made very quickly, from a telephone call to Nicol at his home in West London inviting him to attend an audition/rehearsal at [[Abbey Road Studios]],{{sfn|Harry|1992|pp=45}} to packing his bags, all in the same day.{{sfn|Norman|1993|pp=231}} At a press conference a reporter mischievously asked John Lennon why [[Pete Best]], who had been the Beatles' previous drummer for two years but dismissed by the group on the eve of stardom, was not being given the opportunity of replacing Ringo, to which Lennon replied: \"He's got his own group [Pete Best & the All Stars], and it might have looked as if we were taking him back, which is not good for him.\"{{sfn|Badman|2000|pp=103}}\n\n[[File:The Beatles (with Jimmy Nicol) 1964 001.png|thumb|left|McCartney, Harrison, Lennon, and Nicol in the [[Netherlands]] on 5 June 1964]]\nNicol's first concert with the Beatles took place just 27 hours later on 4 June at the KB Hallen in [[Copenhagen, Denmark]]. He was given the distinctive Beatle [[moptop]] hairstyle, put on Ringo's suit and went on stage to an audience of 4,500 Beatles fans. McCartney recalled: \"He was sitting up on this rostrum just eyeing up all the women. We'd start '[[She Loves You]]': [counting in] 'one, two', nothing, 'one, two', and still nothing!\" Their set was reduced from eleven songs to ten, dropping Ringo's vocal spot of \"[[I Wanna Be Your Man]]\".{{sfn|Mojo|2002|pp=108}} McCartney teasingly sent Starr a telegram saying: \"Hurry up and get well Ringo, Jimmy is wearing out all your suits.\"{{sfn|Harry|1992|pp=484}} Commenting later on the fickle nature of his brief celebrity, Nicol reflected: \"The day before I was a Beatle, girls weren't interested in me at all. The day after, with the suit and the Beatle cut, riding in the back of the limo with John and Paul, they were dying to get a touch of me. It was very strange and quite scary.\" He was also able to shed some light on how they passed the time between shows: \"I thought I could drink and lay women with the best of them until I caught up with these guys.\"{{sfn|Q|2010|pp=56}}\n\nIn the [[Netherlands]], Nicol and Lennon allegedly spent a whole night at a brothel.{{sfn|Mojo|2002|pp=108}} Lennon said: \"It was some kind of scene on the road. [[Satyricon]]! There's photographs of me grovelling about, crawling about Amsterdam on my knees, coming out of whorehouses, and people saying 'Good morning John'. The police escorted me to these places because they never wanted a big scandal. When we hit town, we hit it \u2013 we were not pissing about. We had [the women]. They were great. We didn't call them groupies, then; I've forgotten what we called them, something like 'slags'.\"{{sfn|Q|2010|pp=56}}{{sfn|The Beatles|2000|pp=139}} By then the Beatles were becoming more restricted by their increasing fame and spending most of their free time inside hotel suites. But Nicol discovered that, aside from acting as a Beatle, he could behave much as any tourist could: \"I often went out alone. Hardly anybody recognised me and I was able to wander around. In Hong Kong, I went to see the thousands of people who live on little boats in the harbour. I saw the refugees in [[Kowloon]], and I visited a nightclub. I like to see life. A Beatle could never really do that.\"{{sfn|Badman|2000|pp=110}}\n\nNicol played a total of eight shows until Starr rejoined the group in Melbourne, Australia, on 14 June. He was unable to say goodbye to the Beatles as they were still asleep when he left, and he did not want to disturb them. At Melbourne Airport, Epstein presented him with a cheque for \u00a3500 and a gold [[Eterna|Eterna-matic]] wrist watch inscribed: \"From the Beatles and Brian Epstein to Jimmy \u2013 with appreciation and gratitude.\"{{sfn|Harry|1992|pp=484}} George Martin later paid tribute to Nicol whilst recognising the problems he experienced in trying to readjust to a normal life again: \"Jimmie Nicol was a very good drummer who came along and learnt Ringo's parts very well. He did the job excellently, and faded into obscurity immediately afterwards.\"{{sfn|The Beatles|2000|pp=139}} Paul McCartney acknowledged: \"It wasn't an easy thing for Jimmy to stand in for Ringo, and have all that fame thrust upon him. And the minute his tenure was over, he wasn't famous any more.\" Nicol himself expressed his disillusionment several years later: \"Standing in for Ringo was the worst thing that ever happened to me. Until then I was quite happy earning \u00a330 or \u00a340 a week. After the headlines died, I began dying too.\"{{sfn|Mojo|2002|pp=108}} He resisted the temptation to sell his story, stating in a rare 1987 interview: \"After the money ran low, I thought of cashing-in in some way or other. But the timing wasn't right. And I didn't want to step on the Beatles' toes. They had been damn good for me and to me.\"\n\n==Later career and life==\nNicol reformed the Shubdubs, renaming themselves Jimmy Nicol and the Shubdubs. They released two singles \"Husky\"/\"Don't Come Back\", followed by \"Humpty Dumpty\"/\"Night Train\"; neither of which was a commercial success. He was later called upon to again stand in for an ailing drummer when Dave Clark of [[The Dave Clark Five]] fell ill and Nicol's band, Jimmy Nicol and the Shubdubs, filled in for The Dave Clark Five in [[Blackpool, Lancashire]].{{sfn|Harry|1992|pp=484}} Whilst there Nicol was reminded of just how popular, albeit briefly, he had been as a stand-in Beatle; receiving a bundle of 5,000 fan letters passed on to him from an Australian radio disc jockey. Nicol sent a message back thanking the fans, promising that he would one day return to Australia permanently.{{sfn|Harry|1992|pp=484}} He was later reunited with the Beatles when his band appeared on the same bill as them and [[The Fourmost]] on 12 July 1964 at the [[Brighton Hippodrome|Hippodrome]] in [[Brighton]]. In 1965 Nicol declared bankruptcy with debts of \u00a34,066, nine months after being a temporary Beatle.{{sfn|Mojo|2002|pp=108}} Later that year he joined the successful Swedish group [[the Spotnicks]], recording with them and twice touring the world. He left them in 1967, spending time in Mexico studying [[samba]] and [[bossa nova]] rhythms, whilst also diversifying into business. In 1975 he returned to England and became involved with housing renovations. In 1988 it was rumoured that Nicol had died,{{sfn|pmouse.nl|2010}}, the year after making his final interview and four years after his 1984 appearance at a Beatles convention in [[Amsterdam]], but an article in 2005 by the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' claimed that he was still alive and living in London, refusing to do any interviews or talk about his tenure with the Beatles. It was later asserted by the same source that he had moved to [[Mexico]] in 2013 with his then-wife and was still living there as of 2017, despite family and friends having no contact with him.<ref>Daily Mail, 2017</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nDuring Nicol's brief time with the Beatles both Lennon and McCartney would often ask him how he felt he was coping, to which his reply would usually be \"It's getting better\". Three years later McCartney was walking his dog, Martha, with [[Hunter Davies]], the Beatles official biographer, when the sun came out. McCartney remarked that the weather was \"getting better\" and began to laugh, remembering Nicol. This event inspired the song \"[[Getting Better]]\" on 1967's ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]''.{{sfn|Miles|1998|pp=313}} McCartney again makes reference to Nicol on the ''[[Let It Be (Beatles album)|Let It Be]]'' tapes from 1969, saying: \"I think you'll find we're not going abroad 'cause Ringo just said he doesn't want to go abroad. You know, he put his foot down. Although Jimmie Nicol might go abroad.\"  \n\nWhile appearing on the radio show ''Fresh Air'' hosted by [[Terry Gross]] in April 2016, [[Tom Hanks]] noted that he was at least partly influenced by Jimmie Nicol's experience with the Beatles when he wrote the script for his 1996 feature film ''[[That Thing You Do!]]''<ref name=\"fa\">{{Cite AV media| time=12:46 |work=[[Fresh Air]] |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=April 26, 2016 |title=Tom Hanks Says Self-Doubt Is 'A High-Wire Act That We All Walk'}}</ref>\n\n==Discography and performance history==\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n!1950s\n|colspan=2| \n*Choir boy at Honeywell Road School, [[Wandsworth]], in London.\n*The [[Boys' Brigade]] (percussion).\n*[[Army Cadet Force|Army Cadet]] [[Military Band]] (percussion and xylophone).\n*For a short time, Nicol also worked as a drum repairer for (UK) musical instrument distributor ''Boosey & Hawkes''.\n|-\n!1957\u20131958\n|colspan=2| Colin Hicks & The Cabin Boys. (Colin Hicks is the younger brother of British rock 'n' roll star [[Tommy Steele]]).\n:Singles released:\n:*Pye 7N15114 \"Wild Eyes And Tender Lips\" / \"Empty Arms Blues\"\n:*Pye 7N15125 \"La Dee Dah\" / \"Wasteland\"\n:*Pye 7N15163 \"Little Boy Blue\" / \"Jamabalaya\"\n|-\n!1959\u20131960\n|colspan=2| [[Vince Eager]] and the Quiet Three.\n|-\n!1960\n|colspan=2| [[Oscar Rabin Band]].\n|-\n!1961\n|colspan=2| [[Cyril Stapleton]] Big Band.\n|-\n!1961\u20131963\n|colspan=2| Session work (including jobs with musicians from the orchestras of [[Ted Heath (bandleader)|Ted Heath]] and [[Johnny Dankworth]]).\n|-\n!1964 || \n| The Shubdubs.\n:Singles released:\n:* \"Humpty Dumpty\" / \"Night Train\" \u2013 [[Pye Records|Pye]] 7N15623 2/1964 / US: Mar\u2013Mar Records 313 1964\n:* \"Husky\" / \"Please Come Back\" \u2013 Pye 7N15666 6/1964 (credited to 'Jimmy Nicol')\n:* \"Baby Please Don't Go\" / \"Shubdubery\" \u2013 Pye 7N15699 10/1964\n|-\n!1964 || April / May\n| Touring with [[Georgie Fame]] and The Blue Flames.\n|-\n!1964 || June\n| The Beatles (as temporary stand in for Ringo Starr).\n*4 June 1964: KB Hallen, Copenhagen, Denmark.\n*5 June 1964: Treslong, Hillegom, the Netherlands, (recording TV show, VARA).\n*6 June 1964: Auction Hall (Veilinghal), Blokker, the Netherlands.\n*9 June 1964: Princess Theatre, [[Kowloon]], Hong Kong.\n*12 June 1964: [[Centennial Hall, Adelaide]], Australia.\n*13 June 1964: Centennial Hall, Adelaide, Australia.\n|-\n!1964\u20131965\n|colspan=2| Touring as: Jimmy Nicol & The Shubdubs\n:Solo single release as: The Sound of Jimmy Nicol\n:*\"Sweet Clementine\" / \"Roaring Blue\" \u2013 Decca F12017\n|-\n!1965\u20131967\n|colspan=2| [[The Spotnicks]].\n:Single release by: The Spotnicks Introducing Jimmie Nicol \n:*\"Husky\" / \"Drum Diddley\" \u2013 SweDisc SWES 1111\n|-\n!1967\n|colspan=2| Nicol lived in Mexico working with [[samba]] & [[bossa nova]] groups. He married and had a son, Howard, who in the 1990s won an award for his work as sound engineer on a BBC collection of Beatles recordings.\n|-\n!1969\n|colspan=2|Jimmie Nicol Show:\n:*\"Jumpin' Jack Flash\" / \"Era Psicodelica Del A Go Go\" \u2013 Discos Orfeon LP-E-12-623 (Mexico)(LP) (Sung in Spanish).\n|-\n!1971\n|colspan=2|\"Blue Rain\" (Mexican rock group recording in Nicol's house).\n|}\nInformation compiled from {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111091533/http://www.pmouse.nl/nicol |date=11 January 2012 }}\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[Scot Halpin]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=22em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book\n|last=Norman\n|first=Philip\n|authorlink=Philip Norman (author)\n|year=2009\n|title=John Lennon\n|publisher=Harper\n|location=London\n|isbn=978-0-00-719742-2\n|ref=harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Badman\n|first=Keith\n|year=2000\n|title=The Beatles Off The Record\n|ref=harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|author=The Beatles\n|year=2000\n|authorlink=The Beatles\n|title=The Beatles Anthology\n|publisher=Cassell & Co\n|location=London\n|isbn=0-304-35605-0\n|ref=harv\n}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Harry\n|first=Bill\n|year=1992\n|authorlink=Bill Harry\n|title=The Ultimate Beatles Encyclopedia\n|publisher=Virgin Books\n|